<FIRST>r a AM-Obit-Goff     05-20 0298</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Goff,0307</SECOND>
<HEAD>Irving Goff, Member of 1930s Lincoln Brigade, Dies at 77</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Irving Goff, who fought Spanish fascists as a
guerrilla in the famed Lincoln Brigade of the 1930s and later
became a decorated hero in World War II, has died at age 77 after a
longtime heart condition.
   Goff, who died Wednesday at a Los Angeles convalescent hospital,
will be buried at Arlington National Cemetery in Washington
sometime next week, said his brother, John Goff. No funeral was
planned.
   The Abraham Lincoln Brigade, young political activists concerned
about spreading fascism in Europe, was immortalized by Ernest
Hemingway in ``For Whom the Bell Tolls.''
   Goff, who grew up on New York's Lower East Side, said he learned
about the Lincoln Brigade in 1936. ``I got a passport and joined up
in New York,'' he said in a 1986 interview.
   He and 200 others, some of them leading American intellectuals,
were soon on an ocean liner bound for the Spanish Civil War.
   Within days of their arrival, during a march across the Pyrenees
mountains from France, Goff and other American volunteers blew up a
train carrying Italian soldiers to the front to fight Goff's fellow
Loyalists.
   Goff fought behind enemy lines, usually with a cache of dynamite
as his primary weapon. He finished the civil war relatively
unscathed, suffering only from a case of scurvy, but half the
3,300-man brigade perished in the struggle.
   During World War II, Goff served with the Army's Office of
Strategic Services, forerunner of the CIA, and fought in Germany,
North Africa and Italy. He was discharged as a captain and awarded
a Legion of Merit.
   Following the war, Goff settled in Los Angeles and became a
salesman for a printing supply firm. He married and had two
children.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
