<FIRST>r a PM-Lites     05-20 0507</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lites,0525</SECOND>
<HEAD>On the Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Essex Community College students searching for
a class to fill out their schedule next fall may want to wake up
and smell the coffee.
   G. Stewart Eidel said his Essence of Coffee class ``will give
the students a better feeling for the beverage.''
   Eidel said the high price of coffee _ up to $1 for a cup of
basic coffee, and $2.50 to $3.50 for cappuccino and espresso _ has
forced restaurant owners and restaurant management schools to give
coffee a second look.
   The class, which will focus on coffee roasting, grinding and
brewing, is financed by a grant from the non-profit International
Coffee Organization, which is dedicated to increasing U.S. coffee
consumption.
   ``Coffee has become a big deal recently,'' Eidel said. ``For
one, the consumption of coffee has fallen in the U.S. over the last
10 years.''
   The restaurant industry has responded by emphasizing specialty
blends in an effort to increase demand, Eidel said.
   ``We are seeing the trend to gourmet coffees, yuppie coffees and
flavored coffees such as hazelnut,'' he said. ``Coffee is usually
the last item served with a dinner, so it is the most important
part of the meal.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>KANSAS CITY, Kan. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Midwestern gamblers can go to class
before going to the track.
   Officials building a dog-racing track in the western part of the
city are teaching a course, Intro to Parimutuel Wagering, at the
Kansas City, Kan., Community College.
   The class will include instruction on the history of dog racing
and how dogs are trained. Information on how much money to take to
the track, and how to bet will be passed out. Students will be
taught how to read a racing program and about theories for picking
winners.
   No college credit will be given for the course, said school
official Sue Courtney. And just so no one thinks the college has
gone to the dogs, a class in horse racing will be offered next year.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PETERSBURG, N.D. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Unity High School's Class of '89 all
agreed on what color their graduation gowns should be. The all-girl
class of 10 picked pink.
   ``This is a pretty special class,'' Superintendent Basil Duffy
said Friday as he and others at the tiny school prepared for
graduation ceremonies.
   Duffy said the school, which serves the farming communities of
Niagara, Petersburg and Dahlen in northeastern North Dakota, has
never before had either an all-girl or all-boy class.
   Members of the class acknowledge there have been some drawbacks
to life without boy classmates. For one thing, they were unable to
crown a king at the Snow Ball dance this year.
   But as they prepared to graduate, the young women say they'll
miss the camaraderie they've enjoyed and their friends at Unity, a
school of only 34 students in ninth through twelfth grades.
   All 10 plan to further their education, either at trade or
business schools or four-year universities. Three of the 10 are
engaged to be married and a fourth ``is promised.''
</TEXT>
