<FIRST>r i PM-TiananmenSquare     05-20 0311</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Tiananmen Square,0318</SECOND>
<HEAD>In Times of Turmoil or Celebration, Chinese Flock to Tiananmen Square</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Saturday AMs report.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tiananmen Square, the symbolic center of Chinese
political power, originally was built in 1651, in the early Qing
Dynasty. The Communist government quadrupled its size in 1958 to
about 100 acres.
   The square, where tens of thousands of Chinese have demonstrated
for political reforms this month, is almost as large as the
106-acre Washington Monument grounds in Washington, D.C.
   In the middle of the square is the monument to the heroes of the
revolution.
   At the south end are the mausoleum where Mao Tse-tung lies in
state and Qianmen, or ``front gate'' to the Forbidden City, a kind
of pre-gate that in the past was the entrance to the road leading
to the main gate of the palace.
   On the west and east are two massive monuments to socialist
architecture, the Great Hall of the People and the Museum of
Chinese History and the Revolution.
   To the north, across the six-lane Changan Avenue, is the
entrance to the Forbidden City, former palace for China's imperial
family.
   In normal times, Tiananmen is a favorite spot for Chinese _
accustomed to cramped quarters _ to take a leisurely stroll under
wide-open skies. The square is always crowded with tourists from
outside Beijing, families on Sunday outings or young couples.
   It also brings people together in times of turmoil or
celebration. A million people were said to have crammed into the
square on several occasions during the radical leftist 1966-76
Cultural Revolution to hear the words of Chairman Mao.
   Tens of thousands more flocked to the square to mourn the death
of the beloved Premier Chou En-Lai in 1976, and in 1984, 1 million
stood in the square to mark the 35th anniversary of the People's
Republic.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
