<FIRST>r a PM-Names     05-20 0770</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Names,0799</SECOND>
<HEAD>Names in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY14</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TARRYTOWN, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actress Elizabeth Taylor was the first
choice of the late Aristotle Onassis, but her love for Richard
Burton could not be overcome. So the Greek shipping magnate chose
Jacqueline Kennedy instead, says an author.
   C. David Heymann, author of ``A Woman Named Jackie,'' said
Onassis' daughter, Christina, told him about her father's desire to
marry Taylor.
   Heymann said Christina Onassis called him shortly before her
sudden death in Buenos Aires last November.
   ``Christina told me her father liked Liz a great deal. After
all, she was a great beauty and he liked the fact she had a
terrific sense of humor,'' Heymann said. ``Christina said if it
hadn't been for Burton, Onassis probably would have married Liz.''
   Christina told Heymann she wasn't sure Onassis ever asked the
movie star to marry him but said, ``knowing my father _ yes.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>OVIEDO, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet President Mikhail Gorbachev and
European Commission head Jacques Delors have won the 1989 Prince of
Asturias Prize for International Cooperation.
   Jury Chairman Leopoldo Calvo Sotelo, a former centrist prime
minister, said Friday the men were honored ``for their efforts over
the last few years to promote international cooperation and
eliminate barriers to understanding among nations.''
   The prize is among eight annually awarded by the foundation
named for the heir to the Spanish throne.
   Gorbachev, who became secretary-general of the Soviet Communist
Party four years ago, has won acclaim for his efforts to reduce
East-West tension and reach disarmament agreements.
   Delors, a former French Socialist finance minister, has been a
major force behind plans to create a single European market within
the 12-nation European Economic Community by 1993 and a promoter of
greater cooperation between Western and Eastern Europe.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CLINTON, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bernard Sanders, the former socialist mayor
of Burlington, Vt., will teach next year at Hamilton College.
   Sanders, 47, has accepted a position as a visiting professor for
the spring 1990 semester at the college in upstate New York, school
spokeswoman Helen Burns said Friday.
   A self-described socialist, he will teach sociology courses
dealing with urban problems and democratic socialism.
   Sanders spent eight years as mayor of Vermont's largest city
before leaving office to run for Vermont's lone seat in the House
of Representatives. Running as an independent, he finished a close
second to Republican Peter Smith.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actor Todd Bridges reported suffering knee
and back injuries in a traffic accident while riding in a Sheriff's
Department jail van to a bail hearing on an attempted murder
charge, officials said.
   Bridges faces the charges, along with a second defendant, for a
Feb. 2 shooting in a reputed south-central Los Angeles drug den.
The victim, Kenneth Clay, survived and later identified his
attackers, authorities said.
   The accident involving the van and a flatbed truck occurred
Friday morning at a downtown intersection, said city police
spokesman Don Lawrence. He said he could provide no details about
the accident.
   Bridges, who was the only inmate in the van, complained of knee
and back injuries, Lawrence said. The 23-year-old actor was listed
in stable condition in the jail ward at the County-USC Medical
Center, said Deputy Sean Ruiz.
   No other injuries were reported in the accident, authorities
said.
   Bridges was a co-star in the NBC comedy series, ``Diff'rent
Strokes,'' and appeared in ABC's ``Fish'' as well as various
installments of ``Circus of the Stars.''
   Bridges pleaded innocent to the charge in March and was bound
over for trial in Superior Court. Municipal Judge David Horwitz,
who presided over the preliminary hearing, refused to reduce
Bridges' $2 million bail.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Brigitte Bardot, the French actress turned animal
rights' crusader, returned to the airwaves as host of a series of
programs exposing abuse of animals.
   The first installment of ``SOS Animaux,'' which was broadcast
Friday, documented the slaughter of elephants in Africa, prized by
poachers for their valuable ivory tusks.
   Miss Bardot, 54, who played the blond seductress in ``And God
Created Woman,'' gave up stardom in 1973.
   Since then, she has lived virtually as a recluse in her Riviera
estate, surrounded by dozens of pets, making public appearances
only to promote animal protection.
   Miss Bardot said she was happy to put her name behind a good
cause.
   ``I don't care about my reputation, but I'm delighted to use my
name because it helps me to do something very important,'' she said
in an interview published in this week's issue of the magazine
Paris-Match. ``I have to, because the massacre of animals has
become an industrial and economic issue.''
