<FIRST>r w PM-Senators'Finances     05-20 0666</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Senators' Finances,650</SECOND>
<HEAD>Despite Controversy, Most Senators Accept Speaking Fees</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Most members of the U.S. Senate accepted
speaking fees last year from groups interested in legislative
favors, according to financial disclosure statements for 1988.
   Only 10 of the 95 senators who have released their 1988
financial disclosure statements refused honoraria. According to
separate calculations by the Common Cause lobbying group, honoraria
totaled $2.7 million.
   Among those to accept the payments:
   _Sam Nunn, D-Ga., chairman of the Senate Armed Services
Committee, accepted $6,000 in honoraria from the defense industry.
   _Jake Garn, R-Utah, former chairman and now senior Republican on
the Senate Banking Committee, reported $16,000 in honoraria from
the financial industry.
   _Dave Durenberger, R-Minn., a member of the Senate Finance
Committee, which oversees major health programs, accepted $11,100
in honoraria from that industry. The Smokeless Tobacco Council also
paid him a $2,000 speaking fee.
   _Bennett Johnston, D-La., chairman of the Senate Energy and
Natural Resources Committee, accepted $10,000 for speeches to the
energy industry and a trip to Alaska subsidized by oil, gas and
forestry companies.
   _Timothy Wirth, D-Colo., a member of the Senate Banking
Committee, reported receiving $10,000 in just two days from the
financial industry.
   _Thomas Daschle, D-S.D., a member of the agriculture committee,
accepted a weekend trip to the Kentucky Derby from the Brown and
Williamson tobacco company, plus a $2,000 honorarium.
   Senators are allowed to keep honoraria equal to 40 percent of
their regular salaries of $89,500. Many earned much more than that,
but gave the excess to charity to stay under the limit.
   No limits are imposed on book royalties, and Senate Majority
Leader George J. Mitchell, D-Maine, earned $22,500 in royalties
from ``Men of Zeal,'' a book on the Iran-Contra affair that he
wrote with his Maine colleague, Republican Sen. William Cohen.
   Cohen's $25,763 in royalties also included some still coming in
from a novel he wrote with ex-Sen. Gary Hart.
   The disclosure forms confirmed once again that the Senate is
still populated with millionaires, about a third overall.
   A notably wealthy newcomer is Herbert Kohl, D-Wis., who reported
that his Milwaukee Bucks National Basketball Association franchise
lost $95,000 last year.
   The senators only have to report general ranges of assets and
income, but Kohl is among the richest senators. He listed assets of
up to nearly $28 million and liabilities of less than $2 million.
John C. Danforth, R-Mo., whose grandfather founded Ralston Purina,
listed assets of up to $13 million and no liabilities.
   Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass., reported he was unable to
determine his assets, which are in a blind trust. His income,
however, was at least $607,686. Similarly, the extensive wealth of
Jay Rockefeller, D-W.Va., is tied up in trusts.
   Mitchell is among the paupers of the Senate, listing assets of
just $5,000 to $15,000. Under the rules, that figure does not
include his home.
   Bob Dole, R-Kan., the Republican leader, was better off. He
listed assets of about $293,000 to $691,000. Dole listed $36,000 in
honoraria, of which he donated $31,750 to charity.
   Dole was among those who reported receiving some interesting
gifts. He accepted a series of lithographs depicting ``the heritage
and history of Armenian life'' and a crystal magnolia for his wife,
Elizabeth, now secretary of Labor.
   Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, received from former heavyweight boxing
champ Muhammad Ali an inscribed championship ring. Hatch reported
he considered the ring ``priceless,'' but the gold content was
worth $6,500 and the gem $1,000.
   Five senators received extensions to file their disclosures
late. They were Malcolm Wallop, R-Wyo.; Steve Symms, R-Idaho;
Conrad Burns, R-Mont.; Bob Graham, D-Fla.; and John Glenn, D-Ohio.
   The financial disclosure statements sometimes are only as
accurate as the lawmakers make them.
   The Justice Department on Friday accused Rep. Charles Rose,
D-N.C. in a civil suit of failing to report on his federal
financial disclosure statements $138,694 in loans he obtained over
six years.
   House financial disclosures for 1988 are scheduled for release
on Monday.
</TEXT>
