<FIRST>r w PM-SeabrookLicense     05-20 0467</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Seabrook License,460</SECOND>
<HEAD>NRC Urges Appeals Court to Permit Low-Power Atomic Testing at Seabrook</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CALLAHAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal regulators are urging a federal
appeals court to allow the Seabrook, N.H., nuclear power plant to
conduct low-power atomic tests.
   ``Low-power testing should begin at once to ensure that Seabrook
can begin producing electricity as soon as the NRC has found that
it is safe to do so,'' NRC and Justice Department attorneys said in
a brief filed with the U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals for the
District of Columbia.
   The 20-page brief was filed late Friday in response to plant
opponents' request for an emergency court order blocking low-power
operations.
   On Thursday, the NRC gave final approval for the low-power
license, but said it would wait seven days before issuing the
permit to give the court time to consider the opponents' appeal.
   NRC General Counsel William C. Parler and other government
attorneys dismissed arguments by Massachusetts Attorney General
James M. Shannon and other Seabrook foes as far-fetched and
``simplistic.''
   Shannon, joined by anti-nuclear groups and the town of Hampton,
N.H., contends that the 1,150-megawatt plant 40 miles north of
Boston will never operate commercially because it will never win
approval of evacuation planning. Therefore, the critics argue,
low-power testing would only make the reactor more expensive to
dismantle down the road and pose a health risk to nearby residents.
   But the government lawyers said it is wrong to assume the plant
will not win a commercial license.
   ``There is no reason to believe that Massachusetts' refusal to
cooperate with Seabrook's emergency planning is an insurmountable
obstacle to the full-power licensing of the plant,'' they wrote.
   Seabrook officials submitted their own evacuation plan for the
six Massachusetts communities near the plant after Gov. Michael S.
Dukakis refused to submit state plans. Dukakis says it is
impossible to safely evacuate the seacoast towns.
   The NRC and Justice Department lawyers rejected the opponents'
contention that low-power testing would cost New England ratepayers
more money. They said a delay could result in an economic loss to
the consumers.
   ``If low-power testing should disclose problems that require
substantial time to remedy _ something not expected, but something
that has happened in the past _ delay in beginning such testing
will result in corresponding needless and expensive delays in
full-power operation,'' they wrote.
   ``The public interest lies in avoiding such needless delays in
utilization of poer plants that have been found safe to operate.''
   There was no indication when the court would rule.
   The commission said regulators could issue the license at any
point after 4 p.m. Thursday in the absence of a court order.
   Seabrook officials said they will begin preparations for
low-power testing immediately after receiving the license and start
the tests 10 days later.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890520-0015 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-20-89 0136EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Disclosure-Rose     05-20 0458</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Disclosure-Rose,460</SECOND>
<HEAD>Justice Department Files Suit Against N.C. Congressman over Disclosure
Forms</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rep. Charles G. Rose III, D-N.C., has become
the first member of Congress to be sued by the Justice Department
under the financial disclosure provisions of the Ethics in
Government Act.
   A civil lawsuit filed Friday in U.S. District Court in
Washington accuses Rose of failing to report on his federal
financial disclosure statements $138,694 in loans he obtained over
six years.
   The department sought $30,000 in civil penalties for the six
alleged violations of the Ethics in Government Act. It also sought
an injunction to bar future violations of the reporting
requirements of the law.
   The lawsuit charged Rose, who is chairman of the House
Agriculture tobacco and peanuts subcommittee, failed to report the
loans from his campaign and financial institutions on the annual
disclosure forms filed from 1980 through 1986, excepting 1983.
   Rose's personal loans were obtained both from financial
institutions and his campaign fund, from which he borrowed $52,995,
according to the complaint.
   Justice Department spokeswoman Amy Brown said Rose is the first
member of Congress to be sued under the financial disclosure
provisions of the Ethics in Government Act.
   In a statement, Rose said the lawsuit was intended to ``force me
to file amendments which the House Ethics Committee has not asked
me to file and to pay a fine for amendments (to disclosure forms) I
have already filed.''
   Rose said House leaders have told him they would support him in
the lawsuit because ``the litigation hinders the continued ability
of the (ethics) committee to serve as the primary enforcer of the
reporting requirements for members of the House.''
   In a Feb. 9 letter to a Justice Department official, House
ethics committee Chairman Julian Dixon, D-Calif., and ranking
minority member John T. Myers, R-Ind., said they believed their
committee already had taken appropriate action in the case by
permitting Rose to amend his disclosure form to reflect the loans.
   The financial disclosure forms are filed each year by members of
Congress by May 15 to cover the preceding calendar year.
   The law requires members to report liabilities exceeding $10,000
on the disclosure forms and provides for civil penalties up to
$5,000 for each violation.
   The complaint charged that Rose filed incomplete financial
disclosure forms by failing to mention both new loans and those
outstanding from previous years that totaled more than $10,000.
   In March 1988, the House ethics committee rebuked Rose after
concluding he improperly borrowed funds from his campaign and
failed to report the loans on his financial disclosure reports. The
committee said it found ``clear and convincing evidence'' of House
rules violations, and said Rose's behavior was ``deserving of
reproach.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890520-0016 </DOCNO>
