<FIRST>r i PM-Senegal-Mauritania     05-20 0246</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Senegal-Mauritania,0254</SECOND>
<HEAD>State of Emergency, Curfew Ended in Senegal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DAKAR, Senegal (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senegalese government has lifted the
state of emergency and nighttime curfew declared three weeks ago
during a wave of violence against Mauritanians living in Senegal.
   The lifting of the restrictions, announced Friday in a statement
by the Interior Ministry, apparently was linked to the opening of a
three-day summit of francophone countries Wednesday in Dakar.
   A dispute between peasants near the eastern Senegalese town of
Bakel on April 9 boiled into widespread violence with Senegalese
attacking Mauritanians in Senegal and Mauritanians attacking
Senegalese living in Mauritania.
   Two Senegalese died in the April 9 incident. The Senegalese said
the two died from the bullets of Mauritanian border guards. The
Mauritanians say it was a dispute between Peulh tribesmen.
   Whatever the cause, more than 260 people are thought to have
died in the subsequent violence in the two countries. An airlift
was set up to repatriate tens of thousands of Senegalese and
Mauritanians.
   The state of emergency in Senegal prohibited all public
demonstrations and meetings of a political nature.
   A meeting between the interior ministers of Senegal and
Mauritania held in Bamako, Mali, ended late Wednesday with no
apparent progress toward a settlement between the two countries.
   Mauritanian Interior Minister Jibril Ould Abdallahi and his
Senegalese counterpart, Andre Sonko, met in the presence of Malian
President Moussa Traore, who has been trying to mediate the
conflict.
   No statement was issued after the session.
</TEXT>
