<HEAD>Prosecutors Say North Wasn't Convicted on Immunized Testimony</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The evidence used to convict Oliver North was
gathered independently from the former White House aide's immunized
congressional testimony given two years ago, according to
prosecutors.
   The government made the assertion in a federal court filing
urging rejection of North's request for a post-trial hearing on the
issue.
   In his testimony on Capitol Hill, North detailed many of the
activities for which he was later accused of crimes, including the
three felonies for which he was ultimately convicted.
   North's lawyers want the case against him dismissed. They have
said the grand jury that indicted him and the jury that convicted
him might have been tainted by exposure to his immunized testimony.
Prosecutors disputed that in a response filed on Friday.
