<FILEID>AP-NR-05-20-89 0218EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-HolsterArtisan Bjt   05-20 0568</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Holster Artisan, Bjt,0586</SECOND>
<HEAD>Idaho Craftsman Makes Holsters That Hold</HEAD>
<HEAD>Laserphoto BD1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL ERTELT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>IDAHO CITY, Idaho (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   While her husband was flying Navy
planes during World War II, Bonnie Sparks bought a handicraft kit
for a leather purse to help pass lonely hours in their New York
City apartment.
   When Milt Sparks came home, he was intrigued by his wife's
hobby, which he developed a quarter-century later into the business
of making high-quality holsters sought by gun enthusiasts and
police around the world.
   Wiley Clapp, feature editor of Guns and Ammo magazine and owner
of several Milt Sparks Holsters, calls them ``the very, very
best,'' the first choice of many knowledgeable pistol owners.
   ``I'm sure in the days of Stradivarius there were other violin
makers,'' Clapp said. ``But the virtuoso used a Stradivarius.''
   The dirt-road outskirts of this former gold boom town provide a
natural location for Sparks' shop. The town's wooden sidewalks
would make an Old West gunslinger feel at home.
   But Sparks said the Wyatt Earps of yesteryear wouldn't stand a
chance in a modern-day showdown.
   ``I think that any modern pistolero could clean out the OK
Corral before they could get their guns out of their holsters,'' he
said.
   All holsters are not created equal, it seems.
   ``A holster can quite simply be a matter of living or dying,''
said Mike Waidelich, a Bakersfield, Calif., detective. ``When you
use it 40 hours a week, it needs to be very serviceable. It needs
to be right.''
   Three years ago, Waidelich convinced Bakersfield's 235-member
police force to make the Sparks standard equipment although it cost
about 50 percent more than the holsters they were using.
   Before strapping on a Sparks, Waidelich once had his pistol fall
out of his holster while chasing a suspect. Another time he spent
15 minutes coaxing his weapon out of a poorly designed holster, he
said.
   A Sparks holster is crafted to hold the weapon snugly as an
officer runs or climbs over a fence, but relinquish it when it's
needed, Waidelich said.
   Tony Kanaley, Sparks' shop manager, estimates that 60 percent of
the company's business is from police officers. Clients also
include such celebrities as Hank Williams Jr. and Kareem
Abdul-Jabbar.
   Sparks starts with a stiff piece of vegetable-tanned cowhide.
Kanaley grades and cuts all the leather, and an individual worker
is responsible for finishing the job.
   Sparks said his motto is: ``Do it right.''
   ``Don't sacrifice your integrity to make money,'' he said. ``If
it's not right, if it doesn't save a man's life in a pinch, then
don't do it.''
   In the beginning, satisfaction in a job well done was Sparks'
sole reward. ``Now, I want to make a little money,'' the
72-year-old Sparks said.
   Recently he has been able to leave many day-to-day duties to
Kanaley and his three-person crew, freeing him to travel,
participate in shooting competitions and promote his products.
   Sparks, a former charter pilot and flight instructor, worked
briefly during the late 1940s for a Boise belt and holster maker,
but did not become serious about his craft until 1971 when a fellow
pilot asked him to make a holster.
   Impressed with the results, the friend convinced him there was a
market for well-made holsters.
   The following year Sparks quit his job as a pilot for the U.S.
Bureau of Reclamation and in 1973 moved to Idaho City.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890520-0019 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-20-89 0224EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-TankerSpill Bjt   05-20 0651</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Tanker Spill, Bjt,0669</SECOND>
<HEAD>Alaska Official Says Oilmen Lied at Hearings</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY11</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN S. AKRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ANCHORAGE, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oil industry officials who testified
during federal hearings into the Exxon Valdez disaster lied under
oath to protect their companies' financial interests, a state
official charges.
   The latest skirmish in the battle of blame over the nation's
largest oil spill came Friday after the fourth day of fact-finding
hearings by a National Transportation Safety Board panel. The
hearings conclude today.
   Alaska's representative at the hearings, Bob LeResche, accused
representatives of Exxon Shipping Co. and Alyeska Pipeline Service
Co. of conducting a disinformation campaign to help limit their
liability for the spill's damage.
   ``It's beyond me how officers of a big corporation like this can
just tell things that they flat know are lies, but they're doing it
repeatedly,'' LeResche said in an interview.
   LeResche said he was especially irked by Exxon's suggestion that
the March 24 spill was too large to remove, and that government
officials took their time approving use of chemical dispersants.
   The latter issue arose in litigation over the larger Amoco Cadiz
spill off the French coast in 1978. If Exxon and Alyeska can prove
the government stalled efforts to disperse the oil, it may be able
to escape some of its liability costs, he said.
   ``The dispersant issue is just a phony red herring that Exxon is
floating, and I'm sure as I stand here that their attorneys have
figured out that Amoco got off on just that issue in the French
courts,'' he said. ``It has no relation to the facts in this spill,
but it's the only legal theory that's ever worked for an oil
company, so they're telling lies.''
   William Deppe, Exxon's representative at the hearings, said he
and other Exxon executives had been told not to comment to
reporters.
   Exxon spokesman Joe Tucker in Valdez referred a request for
comment to the corporation's Houston offices, where calls went
unanswered late Friday.
   LeResche also criticized Friday's testimony by Alyeska
officials, who said their contingency plan did not guarantee that a
major spill could be completely cleaned up. For years the industry
promised it could handle a major spill and prevent an environmental
disaster, he said.
   ``Basically what they're saying is, `Yeah, we promised you this
but now we'll tell you we had our fingers crossed when we made that
promise,' '' he said.
   Alyeska, a consortium of oil companies that owns the Alaska
pipeline and Valdez shipping terminal, is responsible for initially
responding to spills in Prince William Sound.
   Company spokesman Tom Brennan denied LeResche's charges.
   ``Our witnesses told the absolute truth on the stand. We stand
behind their testimony,'' Brennan said.
   LeResche, executive director of the Alaska Power Authority, was
named the state's oil-spill coordinator by Gov. Steve Cowper after
the spill. He's a former state commissioner of natural resources.
   Although the overall atmosphere at the hearings has been polite
and non-adversarial, exchanges between state officials and industry
executives have been marked by tension and insinuation.
   A Coast Guard officer who spoke on condition of anonymity said
Friday that state officials were naive or uninformed if they
believed a spill as large as the one in Prince William Sound could
be cleaned up quickly.
   In the day after the tanker ran aground, no amount of boom could
have contained a slick that measured 25 square miles and was up to
a foot thick, he said.
   But LeResche insisted that the industry had changed its tune.
   ``They never said it wasn't reasonable or realistic before,'' he
said. ``They'd been promising everyone in America that it would
work. Now they say, `All along we knew it wouldn't.' I don't get
it.''
   In Friday's testimony, Alyeska managers testified that they did
not know whether the temporary unavailability of 25 tons of cleanup
gear hampered their response to the 10.9 million-gallon spill.
</TEXT>
