<SECOND>PM-Mushroom Recall,180</SECOND>
<HEAD>RETRANSMITTING a0426 to fix cycle designator</HEAD>
<HEAD>FDA Recalls Mushrooms From China</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three separate outbreaks of food poisoning
have led federal authorities to order a recall of
institutional-sized cans of mushrooms from China.
   The 68-oz. cans of mushrooms carry the packer designations
``TM'' in the top line, or ``T3'' or M2'' in the middle line of a
three-line code on the end of the can, the Food and Drug
Administration said.
   The FDA said it is stepping up testing of home-sized cans of
mushrooms from China, but none are being recalled at this point.
   The FDA said it plans to cooperate with Chinese officials to
find the cause of the problem and has offered to send a team of
investigators to that country.
   Outbreaks of staphylococcal food poisoning were reported in a
cafeteria at Mississippi State University on Feb. 13; at the
Peninsula Hospital Center cafeteria in Queens, N.Y.; and a pizza
parlor in Phillipburg, Pa., on April 20.
   FDA said at least 15 people have been hospitalized with the
illness, which causes nausea and vomiting. Several other outbreaks
were reported that may be linked to the mushrooms, the agency said.
</TEXT>
