<FIRST>r a PM-AtlantaMayoral Bjt   05-20 0624</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Atlanta Mayoral, Bjt,0643</SECOND>
<HEAD>Despite Past Scrapes, Maynard Jackson Runs For Atlanta Mayor Again</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SONYA ROSS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Maynard Jackson's enemies haven't forgotten that
he laid off city workers, froze police promotions and snubbed the
city's business administration during his tenure as the city's
first black mayor.
   Still, Jackson appears poised to sail back into City Hall in
October on a wave of populist nostalgia.
   Prominent developer John Portman and Coca-Cola USA President Ira
Herbert are among those who have piled aboard the campaign of
Jackson's sole opponent, Michael Lomax, also a black Democrat and
commission chairman of Fulton County, which includes most of
Atlanta.
   But voters apparently remember Jackson as the lovable, portly
man who married couples, boxed with Muhammad Ali and stood outside
City Hall collecting NAACP donations in a huge cowboy hat.
   Jackson was leading the polls more than a year ago, before he
entered the campaign. That lead ballooned this month: 58 percent to
24 percent for Lomax, according to a poll by The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
   ``The only think I'm going to say is I'm grateful for all the
support I have,'' Jackson said this week.
   The numbers are bad news for many business people, said
Claibourne Darden, a longtime pollster and political consultant.
   ``A lot of them don't want him back,'' Darden said. ``Maynard
had an anti-establishment, anti-business tone during the last of
his administration.''
   Jackson's angry confrontations with business leaders were a
major theme during his two terms, from 1973 to 1981. Atlanta mayors
are limited to two consecutive four-year terms.
   His temper wasn't reserved for the private sector. He fired
1,000 striking city workers in 1977, rehiring most of them a month
later, and froze police promotions after a mid-1970s scandal
involving cheating on promotions tests.
   But among these offended parties, only big business has clearly
adopted Lomax as its choice in the Oct. 3 non-partisan general
election. Local unions and police organizations have yet to endorse
a candidate.
   Campaign disclosure reports show Lomax has received about
$400,000 in campaign contributions from corporate interests over
the past two years; Jackson has yet to release his campaign
contributor list.
   In a recent television interview, Lomax denied that all his
business support could be attributed to anti-Jackson sentiment.
   ``People are supporting me because they believe I have a good
record as a competent, qualified elected official,'' Lomax said.
``There's no biased view on development on my part, neither for nor
against it.''
   Business leaders' main conflict with Jackson came over his
set-aside program, which awarded chunks of city contracts to
minority companies. Firms owned by blacks and women went from
getting 0.3 percent of city work in 1973 to 27.5 percent in 1981.
   ``What I had was a disagreement on issues, primarily affirmative
action, with some people in the business community who said I was
unyielding on the issue and the reality of it,'' Jackson said. ``I
was unyielding. I had to be.''
   Preservation has emerged as a big issue in this year's campaign,
because of recent highway construction and other building that has
changed the appearance of the city.
   Andrew Young, mayor since Maynard stepped down in 1981, has been
seen as favoring developers. Young cannot seek re-election because
of the two-term limit.
   ``I think that a lot of developers have seen in Mr. Lomax a
willingness to sacrifice quality of life for unrestrained growth.
Their money follows their comfort level with Mr. Lomax,'' Jackson
said. ``I do not believe in allowing our neighborhoods to be
destroyed.''
   Tobe Johnson, a professor at Morehouse College, said the
preservation issue is helping Jackson.
   ``The neighborhoods view Maynard as being protective,'' Johnson
said. ``The rap on Michael is that thus far he has not been.''
</TEXT>
