<FIRST>r a PM-Marcos     05-20 0423</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Marcos,0437</SECOND>
<HEAD>Marcos Rallying, But Still Very Critical</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY9</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVE ELLIOTT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Philippines President Ferdinand Marcos
was rallying from kidney, heart and lung failure, but still listed
in very critical condition, a hospital administrator said.
   ``In his current condition, there are periods of high and low,''
Gene Tiwanak, assistant administrator at St. Francis Medical
Center, said Friday. ``I guess you can say this is the time he's on
the upswing, so to speak.''
   Tiwanak said Marcos' fever had subsided and some vital signs had
improved, but the prognosis remained very poor.
   Marcos was on a kidney dialysis machine and a respirator that
was helping him breathe, Tiwanak said. He also was being treated
for pneumonia and bacterial infections.
   ``It is very serious, but he's hanging on,'' said Imelda Marcos,
wife of the 71-year-old deposed leader.
   ``He looks good, stable,'' said Dr. Edmund C.K. Lum, a friend of
Marcos who looks in on the former president every day. ``He will be
OK.''
   Marcos entered the hospital Jan. 15, but he suffered kidney,
heart and lung failure on Thursday.
   Mrs. Marcos made a public appeal Friday to Philippine President
Corazon Aquino to allow Marcos to return to his homeland to die.
   Mrs. Aquino, who came to power when Marcos fled here in 1986,
forbid Marcos' return and said she would not permit him to be
buried in the Philippines, out of concern his presence _ or burial
_ would spark unrest.
   ``I'm confident that sooner or later, the Filipino people will
allow him to come home because there is no reason not to,'' Mrs.
Marcos said.
   Marcos ruled the Philippines for 20 years, many of them under
martial law. After his departure there were several foiled coup
attempts by people linked to Marcos.
   ``The fact is the Marcoses have caused the Philippines a lot of
pain,'' said Tomas ``Buddy'' Gomez, the Philippine consul in
Hawaii. ``They are a bunch of troublemakers, who will utilize this
event as another opportunity for destabilization.
   ``We have every right to protect the state,'' Gomez said. ``We
have every right to protect the advances we have had in democratic
stability and economic progress'' since Marcos fled to exile in
Hawaii.
   The Marcoses are under federal indictment, accused of stealing
more than $100 million from the Philippine treasury to buy art and
real estate in New York. In April a judge ruled that Marcos was too
ill to stand trial, but Mrs. Marcos was charged. She is free on $5
million bail.
</TEXT>
