<DOCNO> AP890520-0026 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-20-89 0518EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i BC-China-PressRetrictions     05-20 0353</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-China-Press Retrictions,0363</SECOND>
<HEAD>With Martial Law Comes Restrictions on Reporting, Photography</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The declaration of martial law in metropolitan
Beijing today was accompanied by strict restrictions on reporting
and photography by the foreign media.
   Mayor Chen Xitong said foreign reporters were banned from
interviewing people on the street, at government offices, schools,
factories and mines. They also are barred from making tapes or
videos that would ``incite or instigate Chinese to march.''
   Photographers were also banned from taking photos under the new
measures.
   No curfew was imposed, however, and it appeared reporters would
be allowed to watch events unimpeded in the streets.
   China, which generally tries to control foreign reporting at the
source rather than interfering with the final product, had not
restricted foreign reporting earlier in the student campaign for
democracy.
   A Hong Kong cameraman reported being taken into police custody
during protests in April, when students tried to storm the
Communist Party headquarters. Several other reporters were pushed
roughly by police, but in general they have been allowed to take
photographs and conduct interviews at will during student marches
and confrontations with police lines.
   The Chinese, however, cut several U.S. television networks' live
transmissions. Normal transmissions from The Associated Press also
went down for several hours this morning, shortly after martial law
was declared.
   The Beijing restrictions are not quite as harsh as they are in
Lhasa, the Tibetan capital and the only other city in China under
martial law. Even before martial law was imposed in Tibet in March,
most reporters were barred. Any one who is in Lhasa when a protest
occurs is barred from even watching it.
   China has expelled foreign reporters in the past during
political crackdowns. Lawrence MacDonald, an American reporting for
Agence France-Presse, was expelled in January 1987 after a
crackdown on previous nationwide student protests. He was accused
of receiving intelligence from a Chinese student.
   A few months later, a Japanese reporter, Shuitsu Henmi of Kyodo
News Service, was expelled on charges of paying a Chinese source
for internal documents regarding the crackdown.
   Both reporters denied the charges.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
