<FIRST>r a PM-DannAnniversary     05-20 0416</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dann Anniversary,0427</SECOND>
<HEAD>One Year Ago Today: Shooting Spree Shattered Wealthy Town</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAULINE JELINEK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WINNETKA, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A year ago today, a disturbed woman walked
into an elementary school and opened fire on helpless students, a
tragedy that still stirs the pupils but has made them ``stronger in
some ways,'' an official said.
   ``This has been a year in which we have grown a lot and in which
we've come a long way,'' Winnetka schools' Superintendent Donald
Monroe said Friday after an assembly.
   Hubbard Woods Elementary School pupils held classroom
discussions in the morning, then sang at the afternoon assembly
held in the memory of Nicholas Corwin, 8, who was fatally shot by
Laurie Dann on May 20, 1988.
   ``For some of the children there is still some anxiety,'' Monroe
said. ``But for the most part the children in the school are
healthy and well _ and they are stronger in some ways. ``We ...
acknowleged the day and acknowledged how well they're doing and how
far they've come in remembering Nicholas Corwin.''
   Administrators also held a special session for parents, and at
least 60 attended, Monroe said.
   ``They all have some continuing anxiety about the safety issues
and the children, but they seem to be dealing with them very
well,'' he said. ``They feel this year has been a positive school
year and that the children feel comfortable in school and they feel
confident in school.''
   A year ago, Miss Dann, 30, spent 4{ hours delivering poisoned
juice and arsenic-laced snacks to her ex-husband, a psychiatrist
and homes where she had worked as a baby sitter.
   She tried to light a gas bomb at a school in Highland Park and
also set a fire at a Winnetka home where she had once worked.
   Then she carried three guns into the Hubbard Woods school and
shot several students, including Nicholas who died below a
chalkboard.
   She fled to a nearby home and wounded a young man, then fatally
shot herself.
   Miss Dann was being treated for mental illness, but her motive
for the rampage remains unknown.
   School officials tightened security after the shooting, locking
all doors except one during school hours and requiring parents and
other visitors to have identification tags.
   The tragedy also sparked debate over gun control in suburbs
along the Lake Michigan shore. Three suburbs in the past three
months have banned the possession of handguns, and a fourth has
banned the sale and manufacture of handguns.
</TEXT>
