<FILEID>AP-NR-05-20-89 0518EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-China-LiProfile     05-20 0486</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China-Li Profile,0499</SECOND>
<HEAD>Premier Emerges As Enforcer In Student Crackdown</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM ABRAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Premier Li Peng, a newcomer in the top echelons
of Chinese power, has emerged as a hardliner after ordering martial
law to quash student unrest in Beijing.
   Li, his voice fired with anger, told the nation that the
``anarchic state'' created by nearly five weeks of student protests
``is going from bad to worse.'' He promised to take ``resolute and
decisive measures to put an end to the turmoil.''
   Hours later, the State Council headed by Li announced that much
of the capital had been placed under martial law for the first time
in Communist China's 40-year history.
   For the student protesters, many who have called for Li's
resignation, the 60-year-old former electrical engineer was finally
showing his true colors.
   Li always has described himself as firmly behind China's
economic and political reforms and says those who classify him as a
conservative misunderstand him.
   He also has denied that there was a serious rift, or power
struggle, between himself and Communist Party General Secretary
Zhao Ziyang, generally regarded as a strong proponent of rapid
reform.
   But since last fall Li and Zhao have taken clearly divergent
paths. Li appears to have come out on top.
   Last September, with the nation's market-oriented reform program
reeling from 30 percent inflation and chaotic growth, Li took
control of the economy from Zhao and announced a two-year austerity
plan. Further reforms will be on hold for the duration.
   The latest conflict, over political reforms, has lead to Zhao's
resignation, Chinese sources say.
   Zhao reportedly favored giving in to student demands for a
dialogue to end a wrenching hunger strike by thousands of students.
Li, apparently backed by senior leader Deng Xiaoping, refused to
compromise, and when the students remained defiant, he called in
the troops.
   Li's image as a conservative dates back to his six years as an
engineer student in the Soviet Union in the 1950s, when he was
imbued with the virtues of central planning. He also spent many
years as an engineer in various energy ministries, where the need
for government controls is more apparent.
   Li was elevated to full membership in the party Central
Committee in 1978, became minister of Power Industry in 1979 and
was named vice premier in 1983. He became a member of the party's
power-wielding Politburo Standing Committee in 1987, and shortly
thereafter rose to be acting premier when Zhao moved over to the
top party post.
   Li was named premier 13 months ago.
   Despite the impression Li is a somewhat wooden technocrat _
unlike the suave Zhao _ he has excellent revolutionary credentials.
   His father, a leading Communist fighter, was killed by
Nationalist troops when Li was three, and the young boy was later
among a group of war orphans brought up by the late Premier Chou
En-Lai.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890520-0029 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-20-89 0529EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-VoyageofDamned     05-20 0388</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Voyage of Damned,0398</SECOND>
<HEAD>Survivors of `Voyage of the Damned' to Reunite</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Survivors are planning a commemoration of the
cursed 1939 voyage that brought 900 Jewish refugees to the Florida
coast where they were turned away by the Coast Guard.
   Most of the 900 passengers on the steamship St. Louis eventually
perished in Hitler's death camps. Their travails aboard the vessel
became known as the ``Voyage of the Damned.''
   About 20 survivors plan to meet in two weeks for a re-enactment
of the trip on its 50th anniversary, this time with a warm
reception at the Miami Beach Marina.
   The group will sail the Florida Princess to the place where the
St. Louis was forced to turn back, then return to harbor
accompanied by a flotilla of private boats and a Coast Guard cutter.
   ``It's a wonderful thing,'' said North Miami resident Herbert
Karliner, who was 12 years old when he and his family were among
the refugees fleeing Germany aboard the ship.
   It left Hamburg, Germany, for Cuba but was denied permission to
dock in Havana. When the passengers turned to the United States,
the State Department refused to make an exception to a strict quota
system for immigrants.
   On June 4, 1939, the Coast Guard chased the St. Louis from the
Miami Beach coast, Karliner remembered.
   ``I saw the coast of Miami Beach very vividly. I was so
impressed with the palm trees,'' he said this week. ``The Coast
Guard came by and chased us off ... Such a big country wouldn't let
900 people in.''
   On the return voyage, the ship's captain stopped in Belgium,
France, Holland and England _ countries that each agreed to accept
a quarter of the refugees.
   Those in England were safe. But within a year, the Nazis had
invaded the other three countries, and about 90 percent of the St.
Louis passengers on the Continent were killed, Karliner said.
   Karliner's family was sent to France. He and his brother went to
children's homes and survived.
   Their mother, father and two sisters were arrested by French
collaborators and sent to Auschwitz. They were never heard from
again.
   Those attending the reunion, organized by Miami Beach Jewish
leaders, will include eight residents of south Florida. The nephew
of the ship's captain, Gustav Shroeder, will fly in from Hamburg.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
