<FIRST>r a PM-MilitaryCrash     05-20 0226</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Military Crash,0233</SECOND>
<HEAD>Navy Jet Crashes In Field; Pilots Eject Safely</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW BADEN, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Navy training jet crashed in a
cornfield but two pilots ejected just before it hit the ground and
escaped serious injury, officials said.
   The jet, a twin-engine T-2, was on a training flight from Little
Rock, Ark., and crashed Friday about 6 miles east of Scott Air
Force Base.
   The pilots were identified as Marine Capt. Donald F. Meisner,
30, of McHenry, Ill., and Navy Ensign Mike F. Mahon, 24, of Towaco,
N.J.
   Mahon was treated for a broken arm suffered when he freed
himself from his parachute harness, which had hung up in a tree in
a farmer's yard.
   No civilians were injured.
   Navy and Air Force authorities said the pilots declared an
``in-flight emergency'' minutes before the crash. They declined to
elaborate.
   The pilots were on a seven-leg, cross-country training flight
that originated in Kingsville Naval Air Station in Texas. They left
Little Rock Friday morning and planned to stop at Scott before
traveling to Mitchell International Airport in Milwaukee for a
weekend ground exhibition.
   There was a small fire when the jet crashed in the 5-inch-high
corn, said Mike Riley, police chief in New Baden, in southern
Illinois about 25 miles southeast of St. Louis. The debris was
confined to a small area, he said.
</TEXT>
