<FIRST>r a PM-NerveGas     05-20 0337</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Nerve Gas,0351</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jury Finds Korean-born Businessman Guilty Of Conspiracy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL J. WAKIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Korean-American businessman has been
convicted of conspiring to send nerve gas to Iran and may face
additional charges of espionage, a prosecutor said.
   A federal jury found Juwhan Yun innocent of a charge of trying
to export the deadly gas sarin, but guilty of conspiracy to export
the gas.
   No shipment took place, but Yun, 48, discussed with an
undercover agent the idea of shipping the gas in 500 quarter-ton
bombs.
   U.S. Attorney Samuel A. Alito Jr. said Yun could be charged with
spying for allegedly having classified documents in his office. The
Justice Department, FBI and military officials were considering the
possible indictment, Alito said.
   The conspiracy conviction carries up to five years in prison,
but under sentencing guidelines Yun faces around three years in
jail, attorneys said.
   U.S. District Judge H. Lee Sarokin set sentencing for July 13.
   ``The last chapter hasn't been written,'' said Yun's attorney,
Stephen Dratch.
   He said he would ask Sarokin to set aside the guilty verdict
because the government was obliged to convince the jury of both
charges.
   Dratch had argued during the nearly three-week trial that Yun
was entrapped by a slick undercover agent from the Customs Service
posing as an arms dealer. He maintained that the agent used
economic coercion to entrap Yun.
   Alito said entrapment was the usual argument in such undercover
``stings.''
   ``Without doing these undercover operations, it's virtually
impossible to enforce the arms export laws,'' he said.
   Yun contacted an undercover agent while seeking to make a legal
shipment of artillery shells to South Korea. He discussed buying
the nerve gas with the agent, but called off the deal Jan. 11.
   A day later, he was arrested near Newark International Airport
at what he thought was to be a meeting with a customs official.
   The prosecution succeeded in showing jurors that Yun had
intended to renew the deal when he was arrested.
</TEXT>
