<FILEID>AP-NR-05-20-89 0629EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-China-PeoplePower     05-20 0479</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China-People Power,0491</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chinese Protesters Feel Power in Numbers</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY WILHELM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Blue-collar workers, white-collar professionals
and students demonstrating for democratic reform swarmed around
troop trucks today in an effort to prevent a government crackdown
from ending their protest.
   It was a kind of ``people power'' different from what
revolutionary leader Mao Tse-tung believed could modernize China
without foreign funds or technology and enable the country to
survive a nuclear attack.
   The people power displayed today was similar to that that pulled
down Ferdinand Marcos in the Philippines in 1986. But the outcome
of today's action was far from clear.
   ``Li Peng, step down! Xiaoping, step down!'' many shouted as
they sped in trucks across the city toward where soldiers of the
27th and 28th armies were entering from the eastern and western
suburbs.
   The chants referred to Premier Li Peng, who signed today's order
imposing martial law in much of Beijing, and 84-year-old leader
Deng Xiaoping, who was believed the main force behind the crackdown.
   Others bicycled or ran to the scene, or pleaded with passing
cars and trucks for a lift.
   At a traffic circle in western Beijing, about five miles from
Tiananmen Square, about 500 people swarmed around 15 army trucks,
each containing a dozen or more soldiers. The soldiers sat
impassively, looking out the back from under canvas covers, as the
protesters earnestly lectured them about the month-old student
movement for reforms such as a free press and rights guarantees.
   ``Maybe you don't understand the real situation,'' a woman told
the soldiers in one truck. ``You haven't been to the square, you
don't know what it's like there.''
   ``We are people and you are people, why do you have no
feelings?'' several recited in unison. ``Your brothers and sisters
may be university students. You should join the people hand in
hand, heart to heart, for you, too, are Chinese!''
   ``We appeal to people in all walks of life: boycott class,
boycott teaching, strike from work and strike from commerce!'' one
youth sitting on the hood of an army truck bellowed through a
megaphone at soldiers. The crowd went wild.
   They went even wilder, clapping their hands in the air, when a
uniformed policeman joined workers on a truck bed. ``Come on out!''
he urged the soldiers, huddled in their trucks.
   ``Army, come out!'' the crowd took up the chant. No soldiers did.
   After hours of haranguing from the protesters, the soldiers
turned around and left in the direction they had come. The crowd
cheered. Some soldiers smiled, waved and flashed V-for-victory
signs.
   Up and down Beijing's main avenue, Changan, students, medics and
other supporters stood by the hundreds at intersections to form
human barricades. In many places, metal and concrete lane dividers
were torn from the pavement and thrown across the pavement to block
vehicles.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
