<DOCNO> AP890520-0037 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-20-89 0631EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Soviet-Georgia     05-20 0217</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Georgia,0224</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tbilisi Children Suffer Symptoms Similar to Gas Poisoning</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Schoolchildren in Soviet Georgia have mysteriously
fallen ill with symptoms similar to those suffered by protesters
who were gassed in a demonstration last month, the official news
agency Gruzinform said today.
   The agency confirmed an earlier report from activists that
children from five or six schools in Tbilisi got sick weeks after a
April 9 clash between demonstrators and troops in the Georgian
capital left 20 protesters dead.
   Many protesters were hospitalized with nerve damage that doctors
attributed to the gas used by troops. Military officials, however,
deny using nerve gas.
   An editor at Gruzinform said the latest victims, including small
children in kindergartens, suffered mild versions of the illness
and none were hospitalized. He did not have the number of children
involved or the dates they became sick.
   At least 20 children who became ill shortly after the clash were
students in a school adjacent to the scene of the demonstration.
Soldiers reportedly chased demonstrators into their school and
sprayed the gas inside the building.
   There was no apparent explanation for the new illnesses. The
Gruzinform spokesman said a commission of deputies to the new
Soviet Parliament was investigating.
   Georgian schools were closing for the summer today on schedule,
the editor said.
</TEXT>
