<SECOND>PM-India,0287</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sikh Extremists Kill Communist Leader, Four Relatives</HEAD>
<UNK>By HARBAKSH SINGH NANDA ^Associated Press Writer</UNK>
<DATELINE>CHANDIGARH, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sikh extremists slipped into the house
of a Communist Party leader in the northern state of Punjab today
and killed him and four relatives as they slept, police said.
   A police official in Chandigarh, the state capital, identified
the victims as Dalip Singh, his wife, daughter, son, and
daughter-in-law. Dalip Singh, a Sikh, was the local leader of the
Communist Party of India-Marxist.
   A news agency, United News of India, said Singh's 2-year-old
grandson and a 3-year-old granddaughter, who were severely wounded
in the early morning shooting, also died.
   The police official in Chandigarh said four Sikhs armed with
Chinese-made assault rifles scaled a wall around Singh's house in
Chak Rahian village and opened fire on the people sleeping in the
courtyard. The village is 135 miles west of Chandigarh.
   The extremists came in a jeep and fled in the same vehicle, said
the official who cannot be identified under briefing rules.
   Mattresses and bed sheets were soaked in blood and bodies were
lying in the courtyard, he said, quoting reports from Chak Rahian.
   The militants, who want to set up a separate nation in Punjab,
previously have killed fellow Sikhs who do not symathize with their
cause. They have also killed left-wing politicians for opposing the
separatist movement.
   Sikhs form 2 percent of India's 880 million people but are in a
slight majority in Punjab, a rich farming state bordering Pakistan.
   Sikhs allege they are discriminated against by the majority
Hindus and the Hindu-dominated national government.
   The 7-year-old bloody separatist campaign has claimed at least
735 lives this year.
</TEXT>
