<BYLINE>By ALLYN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli troops wounded nine Palestinians during
clashes today in the occupied territories, Arab reports said, and
two Palestinian teen-agers died of gunshot wounds suffered in
earlier violence.
   Troops maintained a curfew on most of the occupied Gaza Strip,
keeping more than 600,000 residents indoors for a second straight
day, Arab reports said.
   Merchants in the West Bank city of Hebron staged a general
strike, according to Arab reports, a day after a gun battle in the
area claimed the lives of an Israeli soldier and three Arab
guerrillas.
   The latest fatalities raised the Palestinian death toll in the
17-month-old uprising against Israeli rule to 494. Twenty-two
Israelis have also died.
   Mazni Abu Hatla, 13, died today in a hospital of a bullet wound
in the chest suffered during a confrontation on Friday that claimed
the lives of four other Palestinians in the Gaza Strip, Arab
reports said.
   An army spokesman confirmed four were killed Friday in the
southern Gaza city of Rafah during a clash between troops and Arab
protesters.
   Arab reports said the Rafah demonstration was caused by anger
over a nearly 2-week-long curfew in the area. A U.N. relief
official denied earlier reports that the Palestinians were
protesting a food shortage.
   ``Because of the uncertainty with extended curfews, people may
be anxious about keeping their stocks up but aren't suffering any
real shortages,'' the official said, speaking on condition of
anonymity.
   Most of the refugee-packed Gaza Strip has been under curfew
since Monday, with only a daylong respite on Thursday.
   Also today, 18-year-old Ali Abdallah Mohammed Abdallah died from
a gunshot wound in the head he suffered during a May 10 clash in
the West Bank village of Khader, Arab reports said. The army
confirmed Abdallah's death.
   Violence was reported Friday night and today in four cities and
refugee camps in the West Bank and Gaza Strip, Arab reports said.
   Israeli soldiers reportedly shot and injured two youths in
Gaza's Shati refugee camp. Seven other people were injured by
rubber bullets or beatings in Nablus, Idna and El Farah in the West
Bank, Arab hospital reports said.
   Arab reports said the clash in Nablus, the West Bank's largest
city of 120,000, began as soldiers dispersed a march by 150
activists of the Popular Front for the Liberation of Palestine, a
faction of the PLO.
   The marchers reportedly held signs denouncing PLO Chief Yasser
Arafat for being too moderate toward Israel. The United States
recently began a dialogue with the PLO after it recognized Israel's
right to exist.
