<FIRST>r w PM-US-Soviet     05-20 0282</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Soviet,280</SECOND>
<HEAD>Quayle Accuses Gorbachev Of Making Phony Arms Control Offers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President Dan Quayle has accused Soviet
President Mikhail S. Gorbachev of making phony arms-reduction
offers that amount to little more than ``PR gambits,'' The
Washington Post reported today.
   The newspaper said Quayle told a group of reporters Friday that
``I certainly accept'' and find ``nothing troubling'' about White
House press secretary Marlin Fitzwater's description of Gorbachev
as a ``drugstore cowboy.''
   ``A drugstore cowboy in a sense connotes a bit of phoniness,''
Quayle said. ``And there is a bit of phoniness about the
(Gorbachev) proposals. He is perceived as making radical proposals
out there when they are really marginal,'' particularly the latest
proposal for a unilateral reduction of Warsaw Pact conventional
weapons.
   Quayle said Gorbachev's popularity in the West ``makes it more
difficult for us''' and that having a Soviet leader who is ``very
pleasing to the West, has an easy mannerism to him, who is very
good from a public relations, press, PR point of view, makes it
harder for the U.S. to gain public approval that is needed to
maintain some its defense postures.''
   In another story, The Post today quoted Senate Majority Leader
George J. Mitchell, D-Maine, as accusing President Bush of a
``narrow, shortsighted'' and timid response to Gorbachev's
diplomatic initiatives.
   ``What has concerned me is the emergence in recent weeks of a
negative tone within the administration ... a (tendency) to respond
to Gorbachev's initiatives by engaging in name-calling,'' Mitchell
said.
   He said it is ``particularly non-productive'' to ``say what he
(Gorbachev) is doing is intended to influence public opinion. Of
course it is. So are actions that we take every day.'
</TEXT>
