<HEAD>Soviet Pilot Wounded While Fleeing To Turkey, Wants Asylum In U.S.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with pilot seeking asylum in U.S. No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANKARA, Turkey (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Soviet air force captain was wounded by
gunfire as he fled a Soviet airport in a fighter jet today and flew
to Turkey, where he requested political asylum in the United
States, Turkish officials said.
   The MiG-29 aircraft landed about 5 a.m. at the airport in the
the Black Sea coastal city of Trabzon, said Foreign Ministry
spokesman Inal Batu.
   He identified the pilot as Capt. Alexander Zulyef of the
Mikatachaya unit of the Soviet air force. Zulyef was wounded in the
arm, apparently as he took off from an airport north of the Soviet
Black Sea coastal city of Batumi.
   The pilot underwent surgery and was in good condition at the
Black Sea University Medical School hospital in Trabzon, Batu told
reporters.
   Turkish officials, speaking on condition of anonymity, said they
expected the pilot would be granted political sanctuary.
   Later, as Zulyef was being interrogated by Turkish authorities
in Trabzon, he requested asylum in the United States, according to
the city's governor, Enver Hizlan. The request was forwarded to the
Interior Ministry.
   U.S Embassy officials in Ankara refused to comment on the
incident.
   Batu said the Soviet ambassador was called to the Foreign
Ministry and told that the plane would be returned.
   The incident was not reported in the Soviet media.
   The semi-official Anatolia News Agency, quoting local officials,
said the plane was picked up by Turkish radar and the pilot was
warned to turn back but insisted on landing after lengthy radio
conversation with Turkish officials.
   Anatolia, without elaborating, said the plane was fully armed
and a pistol was found in the cockpit.
   The MiG-29 carries six air-to-air missiles and is able to carry
bombs and 57mm, 80mm and 240mm rockets. There is also one 30mm gun.
</TEXT>
