<FIRST>r i AM-Turtle'sTask     05-20 0215</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Turtle's Task,0219</SECOND>
<HEAD>Giant Sea Turtle Saves Five Passengers Of Sunken Boat</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A giant sea turtle towed five weak
and weary survivors to safety after their boat sank during the
height of tropical storm Brenda, a newspaper reported Saturday.
   The nationally circulated Philippine Daily Inquirer said the
survivors were passengers on the nine-ton vessel Albert, which sank
Tuesday during the storm off the southeastern tip of Luzon island.
   The Inquirer quoted one of the survivors, Emilia Briones, 25, as
saying the five stayed afloat for three days on a makeshift raft
before they spotted the sea turtle.
   They tied the raft to one of the turtle's legs and the big
amphibian towed the craft for two hours before they were spotted by
fishermen in the coastal town of Presentacion, about 200 miles
southeast of Manila, Briones was quoted as saying.
   Briones said there were 10 people on the raft but five of them
were swept away by waves and drowned. Five other passengers of the
Albert were missing and also feared drowned.
   Briones said the survivors released the turtle after they were
rescued by the fishermen.
   A Coast Guard spokesman confirmed the report about fishermen
saving the survivors but would not say whether the report about the
turtle was true.
</TEXT>
