<FILEID>AP-NR-05-20-89 1216EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Afghanistan     05-20 0433</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Afghanistan,0447</SECOND>
<HEAD>President Says He'll Name Commission to Talk Peace With Guerrillas</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SHARON HERBAUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Najib said Saturday he will
appoint a commission to talk peace with Moslem guerrillas but
warned his troops are ready to ``inflict smashing rocket blows'' to
defeat the rebels.
   The guerrillas claimed to have killed at least 10 government
soldiers and shot down a Soviet-built jet in recent fighting.
   Najib said the three-member commission would negotiate with
rebels anywhere and at any time.
   ``This is the best proposal we can make, and what more can I do
for an opposition that claims to hold 95 percent of the country?''
Najib said in a speech to the opening session of the Loya Jirgah,
which is empowered to decide matters affecting the country's future.
   Members include the vice president, prime minister and his
deputies, the Cabinet, and National Assembly members.
   Najib said the commission would be selected by the Loya Jirgah
and would talk to guerrilla commanders inside Afghanistan and to
rebel leaders in neighboring Pakistan and Iran.
   The Loya Jirgah was called into session primarily to extend by
three months a nationwide state of emergency, which was declared
Feb. 18, three days after the last Soviet troops left Afghanistan.
   The Red Army had been in Afghanistan for nine years to back
Najib's troops in their war with the guerrillas, who are supported
by the United States and Pakistan and are based in Pakistan. They
are fighting to topple the communist government and declare an
Islamic republic.
   ``The republic of Afghanistan, by making use of its legitimate
and undeniable right for the defense of its independence and
territorial integrity, will infict smashing rocket blows on the
Afghan armed extremists in Pakistan. There should be no doubts in
this regard,'' Najib said.
   The president added that he would order a full mobilization to
defeat the guerrillas, suggesting every male could be called for
military service.
   He also said he would draw on all available assistance from
Moscow, which continues to airlift food and weapons into Kabul.
   In Pakistan, the guerrillas' Afghan News Agency said 10 Afghan
soldiers were killed and at least 20 were wounded Thursday in a
rebel attack on the city of Jalalabad. The report made no mention
of guerrilla casualties.
   Afghanistan's official Radio Kabul, monitored in Islamabad,
claimed only one soldier died but that 153 rebels were killed.
   The guerrilla news agency said rebels also attacked the military
airport of the southeastern city of Kandahar on Thursday, wounding
11 Afghan soldiers and shooting down a Soviet-built Mig-21 jet
fighter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
