<SECOND>PM-BRF--Crime Cop,0128</SECOND>
<HEAD>Crime Prevention Officer Accused Of Theft</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COVINGTON, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The police department's crime prevention
officer was accused of stealing about $4,800 in cash seized by the
department as evidence.
   Ian Chaplin, 36, a five-year veteran of the Covington Police
Department, was charged with theft after a month-long
investigation, Police Chief Al Strain said Friday.
   Chaplin had the only key to the evidence room and was the only
person with access to anything in it, Strain said. The chief
suspended Chaplin on Friday and then turned on the department's
findings to the district attorney's office, which filed charges.
   The officer resigned Friday afternoon, and the district
attorney's office arrested him two hours later. He was released
Friday night on $10,000 property bond.
