<FIRST>r i AM-SouthKorea-Wages     05-20 0150</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-South Korea-Wages,0151</SECOND>
<HEAD>South Korean Wages Up an Average 17.3 Percent This Year, Report Says</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-South Korea, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   South Korean workers have received
wage increases averaging 17.3 percent so far this year, and more
than 80 percent of labor disputes have been settled, officials said
Saturday.
   The Economic Planning Board warned, however, that the increases
would push consumer prices up 5 percent and make South Korean
exports less competitive abroad.
   The board said the nation's labor disputes, which cost almost $4
billion in lost production, were nearing an end. It said 81.2
percent, or 756 of 931 disputes, had been settled, and that the
rest were expected to be settled soon.
   The wage increases, given by 1,813 companies with more than 100
employees each, were 4.8 percentage points higher on average than
those awarded during the same period last year, the board said.
