<SECOND>AM-Mosbacher-Japan,180</SECOND>
<HEAD>Commerce Secretary Favors Targeting Japan For Possible Trade Retaliation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Commerce Secretary Robert Mosbacher said
Saturday he believes Japan should be among countries targeted by
the Bush administration for possible retaliation in response to
unfair trade practices.
   Under the ``Super 301'' provision of last year's Trade Act, the
administration has until the end of this month to decide on a list
of countries to target for potential retaliatory action.
   Mosbacher, interviewed on Cable News Network's ``Evans and
Novak'' program, said when asked whether Japan should be on the
list:
   ``Well, in my own opinion, they should be one of those
mentioned. Whether they will be or not is a matter of policy debate
that is going on right now in the Bush headquarters.''
   The United States currently has a trade deficit of more than $50
billion with Japan.
   Mosbacher said he did not believe that ``coming down on bad
trade practices'' would result in a trade war and deterioration of
U.S.-Japan relations.
   ``In my view, even though they (the Japanese) are good friends
and strong allies ... it needs to be brought to their attention
that they are not being good trading partners,'' the commerce
secretary said.
