<SECOND>AM-BRF--Spain-Outage,0125</SECOND>
<HEAD>Explosion Leaves 70 Percent of Capital Without Power</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MADRID, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An explosion at an electrical transformer
left most of Madrid without power for two hours Saturday,
interrupting subway service and causing traffic problems as
stoplights went blank.
   An official at the Union Fenosa electric company said a short
circuit at a transformer in northern Madrid caused the explosion at
8:25 a.m. It cut power to about 70 percent of the capital,
including three subway lines.
   Subway cars on the affected lines reached their next station
under emergency power, where riders were told to get off, Spanish
National Radio said.
   Although service was restored two hours later, subways and some
traffic lights remained without power for several more hours.
