<HEAD>Georgia Man Gets Double Life Term For Abduction-Rape Of 6-Year-Old</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MARIETTA, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A landscaper who abducted a sleeping
6-year-old girl from her bed and raped her in a neighbor's back
yard was sentenced to two consecutive life terms in prison, with an
additional 80 years tacked on.
   Brian Richard Ranalli's attorney conceded Saturday that the
32-year-old man wouldn't be released ``anytime soon.''
   Ranalli allegedly left his home after an argument with his
former girlfriend last Oct. 19, went to the child's home and
abducted and raped her. The child lived in the same neighborhood as
Ranalli in an unincorporated area in eastern Cobb County.
   He was arrested a week later. His former girlfriend testified
that he had returned home the night of the rape with bloodstains
and dirt on his clothes. The child was unable to identify Ranalli
by his face but said she remembered what he was wearing.
   The jury deliberated about four hours Friday night before
convicting Ranalli of all six counts against him.
   Before sentencing, Ranalli told the court, ``I have no
recollection of this incident, or I wouldn't have come to this
court to put everybody through it.''
   Cobb County Superior Court Judge Harris Hines said he was
compelled to impose ``a very severe sentence'' because ``the one
place you would hope you would be safe would be within the confines
of your own home.''
