<FIRST>r a AM-NeighborMurder     05-20 0550</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Neighbor Murder,0567</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bizarre Hearing Only Latest Twist in Seacoast Murder Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FRANK BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EXETER, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A prominent citizen is killed by a shotgun
blast while opening his front door in a small, seacoast town. A
veteran police officer shocks the community by confessing to the
crime.
   Last week, former Officer Robert McLaughlin dropped another
bomb. He said his wife pulled the trigger.
   The 48-year-old McLaughlin's testimony was the latest twist in a
confounding mystery in tiny Hampton, N.H., where McLaughlin lived a
short distance from Robert Cushing, a well-known real estate agent
and former teacher.
   Two weeks ago, McLaughlin's wife, Susan, 36, was convicted of
being an accomplice to the murder of Cushing, 63, who was felled by
two shotgun blasts the evening of June 1, 1988.
   Mrs. McLaughlin is appealing the conviction, for which she
received the mandatory sentence of life in prison without parole.
   Prosecutors charge that McLaughlin killed Cushing, with Mrs.
McLaughlin serving as an accomplice, to settle a grudge that dated
to 1976 when Cushing intervened while McLaughin was making a
traffic arrest and told authorities that McLaughin had used
brutality.
   Last week, he made a surprise appearance on the witness stand at
a hearing Tuesday and Wednesday on his motion to suppress his
confession. His murder trial is scheduled to start May 31.
   It took McLaughlin two days, nearly six hours on the witness
stand and dozens of prodding questions from prosecutors and defense
attorneys before he said his wife had killed their neighbor.
   He said Mrs. McLaughlin told him about the death a few hours
after the shooting.
   ``I thought she was kidding,'' the haggard-looking McLaughlin
testified. ``I was advised by her that if I didn't believe her to
go out and look and see for myself.''
   McLaughlin, a Hampton police officer for 18 years, said his wife
threatened to implicate him in the murder if he turned her in. He
said he hoped that if he turned himself in, she eventually would
come forward.
   He also said he told his son, Robert Jr., that Mrs. McLaughin
killed Cushing.
   Robert Jr. had been the star prosecution witness at the trial of
Susan McLaughlin, his stepmother, telling the court that his father
admitted killing Cushing with help from Mrs. McLaughlin.
   Prosecutors say Mrs. McLaughlin helped her husband plot the
killing and stood guard, disguised as a man, while he committed the
crime.
   Robert McLaughlin Jr. sat unemotionally through his father's
testimony last week, seated a row behind Robert Cushing Jr., the
victim's son, who is a locally prominent anti-nuclear activist.
   McLaughlin told police last August that he had turned himself in
because he couldn't stand seeing Cushing's widow sitting on her
deck a short distance from the McLaughlins' apartment.
   Defense attorneys say the statement should be suppressed because
of McLaughlin's impaired mental and physical condition at the time
he gave it. But the judge ruled Friday that the statements will be
admissable.
   McLaughlin, dismissed by Hampton police last fall, has been in
jail since August.
   If McLaughlin is telling the truth about his wife's involvement
in the killing, prosecutors say, there would be no point of
charging her with the murder since she's already serving the
maximum sentence allowed by law on her conviction as an accomplice.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
