<FIRST>r i AM-Sudan-Relief     05-20 0286</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sudan-Relief,0294</SECOND>
<HEAD>Delayed Relief Train Leaves for Southern Sudan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KHARTOUM, Sudan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After a delay of more than a month, a
train carrying 1,500 tons of emergency food supplies left Saturday
for war-ravaged southern Sudan, an official reported.
   Abdul Rahman Hilou, acting relief commissioner, said the train
left Muglad in southwestern Sudan on its way to Aweil, a
government-held town 180 miles farther south, where it will deliver
some of the foodstuffs.
   He said the train, with 48 freight cars, also will unload
supplies in Malwal and Maput, two rebel-held towns between Muglad
and Aweil.
   Organizing the relief shipment is Operation Lifeline Sudan. It
is part of a U.N. effort to prevent a repeat of last year's
disaster when up to 500,000 people perished of starvation and
disease in villages isolated by Sudan's 6-year-old civil war.
   Officials say at least 100,000 people are threatened with
starvation.
   The train had been scheduled to depart on April 15 but its crews
refused to travel through embattled area without an armed escort. A
further delay was caused by government objections to providing food
to areas controlled by rebels of the Sudan People's Liberation Army.
   The $132 million program seeks to stockpile 100,000 tons of food
in southern Sudan by the end of this month, but less than half of
that amount has been delivered.
   U.N. officials have said the operation is a race against time
and seasonal rains that begin in May and turn roads and airfields
into quagmires until November.
   The mainly Christian and animist rebels began their struggle in
early 1983, demanding greater autonomy and economic reforms from
the predominantly Moslem Khartoum government for the three southern
provinces of Bahr el-Ghazal, Upper Nile and Equatoria.
</TEXT>
