<FIRST>r i AM-Lebanon     05-20 0448</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon,0461</SECOND>
<HEAD>Christian Commander Accuses Syria of Sending Jets Over Lebanon</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RODEINA KENAAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Christian army commander Michel Aoun on
Saturday accused Syria of sending jets on ``provocative runs'' over
Lebanon in a plot to continue occupying the war-torn country.
   Gen. Aoun, whose 20,000 mostly Christian soldiers have been
confronting an alliance of the Syrian army and Moslem Druse
militiamen, made the charge in a letter to Arab heads of state,
pleading with them to ``save Lebanon.''
   Aoun claimed Syrian air threats and persistent shelling of the
Christian coast threaten to ruin a cease-fire called by the Arab
League May 11 to halt the latest round of fighting in Lebanon's
14-year-old civil war.
   Aoun, who heads a Christian military Cabinet in Lebanon's dual
government, did not say when and where the Syrian jets made their
overflights.
   But Lebanese media reports said a pair of MiG-17 Syrian jets
twice flew at low altitude over Lebanon's central mountains in the
Christian enclave north of Beirut on Wednesday and Thursday.
   The last known Syrian overflights of Lebanon were in the early
days of Israel's invasion in 1982. Israel claimed it shot down 80
Syrian jet fighters in dogfights over east Lebanon's
Syrian-controlled Bekaa Valley.
   Aoun, who spoke at his shell-ravaged presidential palace in
suburban Baabda east of Beirut, warned Arab heads of state, who
meet Tuesday in Morocco, against ``letting Syria swallow Lebanon.''
   ``You just cannot possibly keep silent about the continuous
crime to starve most of the Lebanese population and force a certain
(Christian) community down to its knees,'' Aoun said.
   Syria maintains 40,000 soldiers on 70 percent of Lebanon's
territory under a 1976 peacekeeping mandate from the Arab League.
But Aoun has charged that the Syrians have lost their credibility
as peacekeepers by siding with the Moslems. He declared a ``war of
liberation'' to drive them out.
   He also clamped a blockade March 6 against illegal harbors run
by Moslem militias south of Beirut in a bid to re-establish state
authority.
   Druse warlord Walid Jumblatt's militia, joined by Syrian
gunners, retaliated by shelling the 310-square-mile Christian
enclave, sealing off its land exits and blockading its ports with
shellfire.
   By police count, 359 people have been killed and 1,393 wounded
since the fighting erupted March 8.
   Aoun said the United States and the Soviet Union were morally
obligated to intervene to stop the Syrian army from shelling the
enclave, home for 1 million Christians.
   He rebutted U.S. Secretary of State James A. Baker III's
contention that the United States cannot do anything to influence
the Syrians in Lebanon. ``The Americans can alter the blockade
against us with one single word,'' he said.
</TEXT>
