<FILEID>AP-NR-05-20-89 1827EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-China-Scene 1stLd-Writethru a0525 05-20 0739</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Scene, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0525,0760</SECOND>
<HEAD>Masses Block Streets to Protect Students</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 4 grafs to UPDATE with virtually every street blocked
by dawn, color. Pickup 4th graf, `Men in...' INSERTS 1 graf after 18th
graf, `At Liu...' to UPDATE with details. Pickup 19th graf, ``Chinese people...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN POMFRET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Elderly women, old men smoking pipes, mothers
with their babies and thousands of students blocked major
intersections early Sunday in a defiant blockade to protect an
8-day-old student demonstration for democratic reform.
   Crowds in Beijing rolled huge cement pipes, six feet in
diameter, in front of roads. Truck drivers moved their flatbed
trailers, packed with coal, into position.
   Every major street going east-west and most major streets going
north-south were blocked. By 6 a.m. (5 p.m. Saturday EDT), the
government apparently had given in to the blockade and students
began moving roadblocks out of the way.
   ``Dawn is breaking!'' people shouted as the sky grew lighter.
``The people have won again!''
   Men in white headbands that read ``Freedom and Democracy''
checked identification cards, looking for military or security
personnel.
   ``It's only natural,'' said a middle-aged man who lived in the
neighborhood. ``We are protecting the people.''
   At Liu Li Qiao in southwest Beijing, thousands of local
residents assisted by students confronted a convoy of 20 army
trucks holding more than 600 soldiers. About 30 trucks with coal
and scrap metal also blocked the way.
   ``The People's Liberation Army belongs to the people!'' the
crowd chanted. ``Patriotism is no crime!''
   Young men climbed on the trucks and talked to soldiers. Some
soldiers laughed and discussed the student movement, sitting back
with automatic rifles in their laps. Others refused to talk with
the students.
   Students clutching microphones spoke to the crowd and the
soldiers from atop the cabs of the convoy.
   ``Dear soldiers,'' said a letter read by a woman in a hoarse
voice. ``Now is the critical time. Listen to the people surrounding
you. Our movement is a patriotic, democratic movement.''
   Liu Li Qiao was the scene of a confrontation between students
and People's Armed Police on Saturday after thousands of people
refused to let soldiers pass. A student involved in the clash said
45 of his classmates were injured when security forces attacked
them with electric cattle prods.
   Sunday morning the crowd was peaceful, but not boisterous.
   ``Who are you going to hit?'' an elderly woman yelled at the
soldiers. ``Are you going to shoot students or the people? I think
you should go home to your families.''
   On Friday night, Premier Li Peng and President Yang Shangkun
announced that China was sending troops to Beijing to end the
pro-democracy protests.
   Early Saturday, Li declared martial law in some areas of the
city, but the government so far has been unable to enforce it.
   ``People's power is unstoppable,'' said a middle-aged man as he
stood with his child near the troop trucks. ``I just can't believe
they would kill our own students.''
   Chinese sources said authorities have brought in army troops
from outside Beijing to carry out martial law because the 38th
Army, assigned to protect Beijing, has refused to suppress the
movement.
   At Liu Li Qiao, the army was from Shanxi. Another army pushed
back from an intersection early Saturday hailed from Hebei. To the
elation of the crowds there, they were forced to retreat early
Saturday.
   On Sunday morning, soldiers again attempted to break through the
people's line. Two city buses, a truck packed with old furniture
and a sit-in demonstration of about 800 blocked the way.
   ``Chinese people have always felt close to their soldiers,''
said one man at the Liu Li Qiao intersection. ``So we must educate
them about what's happening in Beijing. We also have been giving
them food and water. They are our brothers.''
   China army plays an important role in society, responding to
disasters, engaging in construction projects, operating factories,
publishing houses and movie studios.
   Uniformed soldiers can be found everywhere in China and are
referred to as ``Uncle Soldier.''
   On Sunday, many protesters said they felt no emnity toward
soldiers.
   ``They are puppets, like everybody else in China,'' said an old
man as he smoked his pipe and watched the scene at Liu Li Qiao.
``Everybody in their hearts wants democracy and to protect the
students. We are just afraid they will listen to their orders and
not their hearts.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
