<FIRST>u a AM-US-China 3rdLd-Writethru a0568 05-20 0862</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-China, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0568,850</SECOND>
<HEAD>Baker Takes Cautious Approach on China Situation</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: INSERTS 1 graf after 20th graf pvs, bgng: ``The spokesman...''
to add Cheney comment; picks up 21st graf pvs, bgng: ``In Washington...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERENCE HUNT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP White House Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KENNEBUNKPORT, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration said
Saturday it was not in the best interest of the United States to
have ``significant instability'' in China and said Washington did
not want to be seen as encouraging student demonstrators to riot.
   ``What may be happening here is that the economic reforms in
China got out a little bit ahead of the political reforms,'' said
Secretary of State James A. Baker III.
   Meanwhile, in Washington the State Department issued a travel
alert, warning American citizens to avoid travel to China and
urging those already there to stay off the streets.
   ``We recommend that U.S. citizens defer travel to the People's
Republic of China for the next 72 hours,'' said spokesman Adam
Shub. ``Travelers in Beijing are being advised not to leave their
hotels or immediate residential areas.''
   An administration source, who spoke privately, said it appeared
U.S. citizens were not in any danger from the demonstrators, noting
some used a replica of the Statue of Liberty in their protests.
   ``That speaks for itself,'' the source said. But he said the
department had issued the alert to warn citizens against being
caught up in the ongoing demonstrations.
   Baker spoke at a news conference where he reported on talks
between President Bush and visiting French President Francois
Mitterrand. He said both presidents, conferring at Bush's vacation
home, hoped for restraint in China.
   His comments came as hundreds of thousands of students
demonstrating for democracy defied a martial law declaration and
swarmed into the streets in Beijing.
   The Bush administration has refrained from criticizing the
Beijing government for its promised crackdown on the demonstrators.
   Taking a cautious approach, Baker said, ``I don't think it's in
the best interest of the United States for us to see significant
instability in the Peoples Republic of China just like I don't
think it's in the best interest of the United States for us to see
significant instability in the Soviet Union.
   Asked why the United States was not encouraging the students,
Baker said, ``I think we should be expressing our support for
freedom of speech, for democratization and for freedom of assembly.
   ``And that's what we're doing,'' he said. ``I do not think that
we should in any way be seen to be somehow inciting to riot and I
think that we have to be appropriate in our response.''
   He said a news blackout declared by the government was
``regrettable. We wish that that had not been done. We continue to
urge restraint in the situation overall.''
   Baker said it was too premature to conclude that developments in
China have strengthened the hand of hardliners led by Premier Li
Peng.
   ``It's a little bit unclear exactly what the situation is as
between the hardliners on the one hand and those who profess to
support more openness on the other,'' the secretary said.
   ``I think we simply have to wait and see,'' he added. ``I do
think it's fair to say that the situation is unclear and there is a
certain degree of flux.''
   Asked how the United States would view a harsh crackdown on the
students, Baker said, ``that's a very hypothetical qeustion ...
that you can obviously understand why I wouldn't respond to.''
   President Bush's spokesman Marlin Fitzwater offered words of
support for the student-led demonstrations, saying, ``The United
States stands for freedom of speech and freedom of assembly.
   ``The demonstrations of the last few days indicate that the
hunger for change remains strong,'' said Fitzwater, with Bush on a
trip to his seaside home.
   The spokesman said the chief executive had received an update on
events in China during his morning intelligence briefing.
   Meanwhile, Defense Secretary Dick Cheney told reporters in
Cheyenne, Wyo., ``There is very little the United States can do
from a military standpoint and very little the United States would
want to do from a military standpoint'' regarding the situation in
China.
   In Washington, a State Department monitoring group was keeping
tabs on developments in China.
   The State Department also expressed concern about the news
blackout imposed by Chinese authorities.
   ``We are concerned over the interruption of the free flow of
information from Beijing, which has occurred over the past day. We
hope the progress the Chinese have made in recent years will be
sustained and further advanced,'' the agency said.
   ``The situation remains uncertain,'' Fitzwater said. ``Both
sides have exercised restraint and we urge that restraint to
continue. We remain hopeful that a dialogue between the government
and the students is possible.''
   Friday evening, Fitzwater called the blackout ``very
disturbing.''
   ``We urge that it not signal an end to appropriate restraint or
an end to dialogue with the students,'' the spokesman said.
   With martial law declared in some parts of the capital, Beijing
Mayor Chen Xitong said foreign reporters were forbidden to conduct
interviews or make tapes or videos on the streets or at government
offices, schools, factories and mines.
</TEXT>
