<FIRST>r i AM-SriLanka     05-20 0369</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sri Lanka,0381</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report Four Indian Soldiers, Seven Tamils Killed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four Indian soldiers were among 11
people killed in a mine explosion, assassination and mob violence
in the past 24 hours, officials and other sources reported Saturday.
   But none of the attacks was blamed on members of the People's
Liberation Front, an organization of militant Sinhalese battling
both Tamil separatists and the predominantly Sinhalese government.
   The People's Liberation Front on Friday declared a three-day
cease-fire for the Vesak festival honoring Buddha. No violence was
reported in central and southern Sri Lanka, which are populated
mainly by Sinhalese.
   These deaths were reported in Tamil dominated zones in northern
and eastern Sri Lanka:
   A land mine blew up an Indian army truck in a village near the
town of Vavuniya, 135 miles northeast of Colombo, killing four
soldiers. Surviving troopers shot and killed a Tamil rebel.
   The Indian High Commission also said Indian soldiers found the
bodies of three adults and an infant near the port city of
Trincomalee 147 miles northeast of Colombo. It said local residents
told the soldiers the victims were Tamils who were killed by a
Sinhalese mob.
   The High Commission said Indian troopers killed a Tamil Tiger
guerrilla in Vavuniya early Saturday.
   Vavuniya residents, contacted by telephone, said Tamil Tiger
guerrillas assassinated a member of the rival Eelam People's
Revolutionary Liberation Front.
   At least 9,000 people have been killed since Tamil rebels began
fighting six years ago for their own homeland in northeastern Sri
Lanka, an island off southern India.
   It is estimated that militants of the People's Liberation Front
have killed 3,500 Sinhalese who served or supported the government.
   The People's Liberation Front began its deadly campaign after
the government's attempt in 1987 to negotiate peace with the Tamil
rebels.
   Sinhalese militants accused the government of making too many
concessions to the Tamil minority.
   India, the broker in the 1987 peace plan, sent troops to Sri
Lanka to help disarm Tamil rebels but they became the targets of
attacks.
   Most Tamils are Hindus and they compose about 18 percent of the
Island's population of 16 million. The Buddhist Sinhalese make up
75 percent.
</TEXT>
