<FIRST>r i AM-Britain-Fire     05-20 0228</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Fire,0234</SECOND>
<HEAD>Supermarket Burns, Caller Claims Arson Because Icelandic Fish Sold</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NOTTINGHAM, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A blaze damaged a supermarket and
warehouse Saturday, the fire department said, and a caller claimed
it was set to protest the sale of fish from Iceland, which hunts
whales despite international opposition.
   The Nottinghamshire fire department said it knew of no one
injured in the fire, although 21 workers were reported in the
bakery and warehouse in Carlton, near Nottingham in central
England, when it broke out. More than 40 firefighters fought the
blaze.
   The fire caused an estimated $810,000 in damage to the Tesco
chain store, including all the stock in the warehouse.
   Later, a caller to a British Broadcasting Corp. radio station
claimed responsibility for the blaze, saying it was in protest over
Tesco's policy of stocking Icelandic fish.
   The environmental group Greenpeace, which has protested Tesco's
policy of buying Icelandic fish because of Iceland's whale
industry, condemned the attack. A spokesman said Greenpeace was not
involved.
   The International Whaling Commission has declared a moratorium
on the killing of whales to preserve their diminishing numbers. But
Iceland continues what it calls ``scientific whaling'' _ taking a
limited number of whales for scientific research but selling the
meat as well.
   Critics, saying the program camouflages commercial whaling, have
called for a boycott of Icelandic fish. Fishing is Iceland's
primary industry.
</TEXT>
