<FIRST>r i AM-MexicoEconomy     05-20 0277</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mexico Economy,0288</SECOND>
<HEAD>President To Extend Wage-Price Freeze</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Carlos Salinas de Gortari will
extend wage and price controls beyond the July 31 expiration date,
newspapers said Saturday.
   They reported Salinas said Friday the controls must remain in
force to ensure improved living standards for workers.
   The controls went into effect in February 1988 after prices
soared 159.2 in 1987. Inflation was reduced to 51.7 percent last
year.
   Under an agreement, the government pledged to curb spending,
labor to hold down wage demands and business to freeze prices.
   Newspapers did not indicate how long the extension might last,
but some business leaders said they thought it would remain in
effect through the end of the year.
   Salinas, addressing a union conference, also spoke about opening
the Mexican economy to foreign investments, according to the
papers. He was quoted as saying, ``We will pursue the changes that
are indispensible to put Mexico in the vanguard of modernizing
countries.''
   The newspapers also said Finance Minister Pedro Aspe defended
the government's decision last week to encourage foreign
investments.
   They reported he suggested other Latin American nations also
should open their economies to outside investments along with
renegotiating their debt burdens.
   Mexico's foreign debt is $107.4 billion.
   On Wednesday, Aspe announced a $1.96 billion package of loans to
Mexico by the World Bank. The money is to be used for public
projects and to reduce interest payments on the debt.
   On Monday, Commerce Secretary Jaime Serra Puche announced new
foreign investment regulations that open some sectors of the
economy that had been sheltered for years and increases the amount
of foreign ownership allowed in other sectors.
</TEXT>
