<SECOND>AM-Children Shot, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0576,0425</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man, Four Children Found Slain in House</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Eds: SUBS grafs 9-11, bgn `Ms. Mahannah...,' to CORRECT spelling
to `Dubbin' sted `Dubbins.' ^By RICH HARRIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man described as a paranoid drug user
sent his common-law wife to buy cigarettes, then shot and killed
four children and himself in their home Saturday morning, police
said.
   Police tactical unit officers found the body of John Andrew
Dubbin, 31, and those of the children, ranging in age from 1 to 7,
in the living room of a garage that had been converted into a house
in a working-class neighborhood.
   ``It's from hell in there,'' police Lt. Bill Mattei said after
SWAT team members stormed the house.
   The children were identified as Elizabeth Ann Dubbin, 2, and
Albert Michael Dubbin, 1, the daughter and son of Dubbin and his
common-law wife, Elizabeth Mahannah, and Heather Lynn Mahannah, 7,
and Christina Marie Mahannah, 4, Ms. Mahannah's daughters by
another man, a police statement said.
   Each of the children appeared to have been shot once with a
16-gauge shotgun, said Capt. Tony Lanata, head of the homicide
squad. The children were dressed in their bed clothing, said Mike
Elkins, a homicide detective.
   SWAT officers tossed tear gas into the house and entered it
after repeated attempts to communicate with the occupants failed,
said SWAT team commander Lt. Richard Morgan.
   ``We even knocked a window out and threw a phone in there to try
to get him (Dubbin) to come to the phone,'' Morgan said. ``I was
under the impression that I needed to do something in case there
were injured in there that needed aid ... so the assault team went
in.''
   SWAT team members shot and killed a dog that attacked them as
they entered the home, Morgan said.
   Ms. Mahannah called police from outside the house after she
returned from buying cigarettes and found Dubbin and the children
locked in the house, police said.
   ``The wife stated that her husband was very paranoid ... and
that he had fired his shotgun in the house about 5 a.m., thinking
the SWAT was coming to get him,'' said SWAT team commander Lt.
Richard Morgan. He said Ms. Mahannah also described her husband as
a user of cocaine and other drugs.
   Dubbin had been convicted for resisting arrest, burglary and
criminal damaging, Morgan said.
   Neighbors said they knew little about Dubbin, who had lived in
the area only a few months.
