<FILEID>AP-NR-05-20-89 2042EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Namibia     05-20 0341</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Namibia,0351</SECOND>
<HEAD>Says South African Force Will Withdraw Ahead of Schedule</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WINDHOEK, Namibia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   South Africa will reduce its military
force in Namibia to 1,500 soldiers by June 24, an army commander
said Saturday.
   That is a week earlier than the July 1 date set in the U.N. plan
to bring independence to the territory, also known as South-West
Africa.
   Maj. Gen. Willie Meyer, commander of South African forces in
Namibia, said he had ordered the phased troop withdrawal to proceed
at a pace that would leave only 1,500 soldiers in the territory by
June 24 and they would be confined to two designated bases.
   South Africa has not said how many soldiers it has in Namibia,
but it should now be under 12,000 according to the U.N. timetable.
   On Friday, a South African, Cuban and Angolan commission
announced that South African troops and guerrillas of the
South-West Africa People's Organization had ceased hostilities and
returned to their bases, clearing the way for resumption of the
independence process.
   Delegations of the three countries, joined by Soviet and U.S.
observers, said after a meeting in southern Angola they had
received confirmation that South African forces had returned to
their bases in Namibia and SWAPO guerrillas were back in bases in
Angola.
   The three nations agreed in December to the U.N. independence
plan that calls for elections in Namibia in November. The plan
includes the withdrawal of Cuban troops from Angola where they
helped the Marxist government fight anti-communist rebels.
   The process was interrupted April 1, the day it started, when
hundreds of SWAPO guerrillas crossed into Namibia from Angola.
   South African forces left their bases to block the incursion and
Namibian officials reported 316 guerrillas and 27 security force
members were killed in the subsequent fighting.
   Under the U.N. plan, the guerrillas, who have been fighting for
independence for 23 years, will be allowed to return to Namibia,
unarmed, to participate in the elections.
   South Africa has administered Namibia, a former German
possession, since the end of World War I.
</TEXT>
