<FILEID>AP-NR-05-20-89 2045EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-RadnerRemembered     05-20 0495</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Radner Remembered,0510</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Classmates, Professors Remember Gilda Radner</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Obit-Radner</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Betty Irwin remembers the time in high school
when Gilda Radner acted like Chevy Chase, her prat-falling partner
on ``Saturday Night Live.''
   ``There was a play once, `The Mouse That Roared,''' said Irwin,
a classmate and friend of Radner's at The Liggett School in Grosse
Pointe. ``She was upstairs in the dressing room trying to get
dressed. Lee Jenkins was the queen (on stage). Gilda lost her
balance and literally rolled down the stairs and onto the stage.
   ``She began ad-libbing right away. Her and Lee Jenkins just
bounced off one another. Lee sort of said, `Well, she always was a
little clumsy.'
   ``The teacher behind the stage was just having a fit because she
couldn't follow the script. It was really cute.''
   The rest, as they say, was history. Miss Radner went on to
become an Emmy Award-winning star of NBC-TV's ``Saturday Night
Live.'' She died of cancer Saturday in Los Angeles at age 42.
   Miss Radner's talents were rooted deep in her Detroit-area
upbringing, from her skills as a writer and stage performer to her
hospital volunteer work.
   Born in Detroit, Miss Radner attended the all-girls Liggett
school and graduated in 1964. Eighteen members of the 24-member
graduating class held their 25th reunion party two weeks ago.
   ``We all knew Gilda was in the hospital,'' Irwin said. ``I know
if Gilda would have been up to it, she would have been here. We
videotaped (the reunion) but we couldn't get it to her in time. She
had gone into a coma before we could get it out.
   ``We really missed her, and we didn't know she was as bad as she
was.''
   In her freshman year, Miss Radner performed with her school
choir with the Detroit Symphony Orchestra at Ford Auditorium.
   In her junior year, she transferred to Detroit Mumford High
School and also worked as a volunteer at Sinai Hospital.
   ``Actually I was going to teach retarded kids. I used to work
with the emotionally disturbed in Detroit,'' she said in a New York
Daily News interview in 1977.
   She returned to Liggett for her senior year, then enrolled at
the University of Michigan as a drama student.
   ``Her sense of humor was constant and engaging. When she was a
student in Ann Arbor, we sort of got a free `Saturday Night Live'
every day because of that bubbling attitude toward life, and it was
original,'' said retired University of Michigan Professor Richard
Burgwin.
   ``It was a wonderful fountain of wit and joy,'' he said in a
telephone interview from his home in Bradenton, Fla.
   Radner quit school in 1969, he said.
   ``I think she was bored, quite frankly,'' Burgwin said. ``There
are performers who need and want training, and there are others who
are themselves and ready to go. I think Gilda made the right
judgment, what we had to give was not what she needed.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890520-0113 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-20-89 2113EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Ethiopia     05-20 0333</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ethiopia,0345</SECOND>
<HEAD>President Says Coup Leaders Committed Suicide</HEAD>
<BYLINE>BY ABEBE ANDUALEM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ADDIS ABABA, Ethiopia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Mengistu Haile Mariam
said Saturday that three generals who joined in a coup attempt had
killed themselves rather than surrender.
   It initially was reported the three were among officers killed
by loyal soldiers during the attempted coup that began Tuesday.
   Mengistu did not name the generals he said had committed
suicide, but spoke of them as ``agents of our detractors.''
   Mengistu spoke at a rally in downtown Addis Ababa in his first
public appearance since announcing on radio and television Thursday
that the coup had been crushed.
   He told the rally, ``Our detractors and their accomplices never
spared a moment to sow confusion and uncertainity by alleging that
we have failed to achieve immediate results in our endeavors.''
   Diplomatic sources said nearly the entire high command,
including six rebellious generals, were killed during the attempt
to overthrow the government.
   They said the revolt was led by generals humiliated by recent
defeats in Ertirea and Tigre provinces in northern Ethiopia where
different guerrilla forces are fighting for autonomy.
   The revolt began a few hours after Mengistu left for a visit to
East Germany. He hurried back Wednesday to face the biggest crisis
of his 15-year-old Marxist government.
   It was reported Tuesday that Maj. Gen. Merid Negussie, the chief
of staff, and Maj. Gen. Amha Desta, the air force commander, were
killed in the revolt.
   The diplomatic sources said Friday that loyalist troops killed
Maj. Gen. Denissie Bulto, commander of the 2nd Army with
headquarters in Asmara, the capital Eritrea.
   The 150,000-strong 2nd Army, with nearly half of the country's
entire armed forces, had been split into rival factions, according
to the diplomatic sources.
   Mengistu and other officers deposed Emperor Haile Selassie on
Sept. 12, 1974.
   Addis Ababa was calm Saturday although tanks and armored
vehicles remained stationed at strategic buildings. There was no
information about the situation in the rest of the country.
</TEXT>
