<FIRST>u i AM-ECMeeting 1stLd-Writethru a0548 05-20 0571</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-EC Meeting, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0548,0591</SECOND>
<HEAD>British Official Warns of Problems With Rising Dollar</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS thruout to UPDATE with new developments. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALLY JACOBSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>S'AGARO, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   European finance ministers on Saturday
hesitantly took their first steps toward forging common monetary
and economic policies.
   The finance chiefs of the 12 nations of the European Community
agreed to spell out the measures necessary for better coordination
among their governments.
   But they failed to embrace new proposals calling for sweeping
policy changes that would lead to a common currency and central
bank for the trading bloc.
   Britain has expressed opposition to the plan, saying it would
force countries to give up some of their sovereignty to new
institutions.
   ``It is, I think, very glib to assume that you can just go ahead
on this course...without making major changes on the political
front,'' Nigel Lawson, Britain's chancellor of the exchequer, told
reporters.
   These, he said, ``are not changes which we are in any sense
ready to make.''
   Spain's finance minister, Carlos Solchaga, said the ministers
spoke at length and reached ``minimum agreement'' on the monetary
plan at their meeting in a luxury resort on Spain's Costa Brava.
   Dutch Finance Minister Onno Ruding described the discussion as
constructive. He said immediate progress should not be expected.
   The finance ministers, who arrived Friday, meet twice a year in
an informal setting to hash over financial and monetary issues.
   About 200 yards from the talks, about 100 protesters
demonstrated against military spending by the European countries.
   ``Military spending for social spending!'' they chanted.
   Leading off the ministers' agenda was a report released last
month that urged the nations to begin the move toward economic and
monetary union by July 1990.
   It is part of the drive to create a common European market by
the end of 1992. Such a goal would allow people, goods and capital
to move freely among the countries.
   Jacques Delors, president of the European Commission, the
community's executive body, led the 17-member committee that
drafted the monetary report.
   The committee's recommendations would require major changes in
the way in which the nations conduct economic and monetary policy.
The proposed changes were broken down into three phases.
   The ministers agreed community officials should set out what
needs to be done in the first stage, which generally calls for
greater policy coordination.
   They also want more details on the next two stages before
deciding whether to make changes in the Treaty of Rome, which sets
the legal foundation for the European-wide market in 1992.
   Delors insisted that if the governments make the initial moves
toward monetary union, they must complete the process.
   Not to do so, he said, would amount to ``one more failure on the
long road'' to economic and monetary union.
   Delors, asked about London's coolness to the monetary report,
noted there was an internal debate in Britain over European unity.
   He said he awaited a June summit of community leaders ``to make
a final assessment'' on Britain's views.
   British Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher, often at odds with
Delors, has said the community's vision of unity would mean a
``superstate'' of faceless bureaucrats in Brussels.
   The ministers also welcomed a new proposal for smoothing their
widely varying value-added taxes, roughly like sales taxes in the
United States.
   Common Market members are: Belgium, Britain, Denmark, France,
Germany, Greece, Ireland, Italy, Luxembourg, the Netherlands,
Portugal and Spain.
</TEXT>
