<FIRST>u a AM-NavigationSatellite 2ndLd-Writethru a059use0 05-20 0530</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Navigation Satellite, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0598,0539</SECOND>
<HEAD>High Winds Force Postponement of Navigation Satellite Launch</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 5th graf, `No new ..., to UPDATE with launch date set.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HOWARD BENEDICT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Aerospace Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Strong, shifting winds Saturday
night forced the Air Force to postpone the launch of a navigation
satellite designed to tell U.S. and allied forces their location
within 50 feet anywhere on the globe.
   The postponement was announced with the countdown holding at
just four minutes before the intended blastoff time, 7:55 p.m.
   ``The upper level winds are too variable to risk a launch of the
Air Force Delta 2 rocket through that environment tonight,'' said
Lt. Col. Ron Rand, the Air Force launch commentator.
   The countdown had proceeded perfectly throughout the day while
weathermen kept a close watch on the upper altitudewinds. Rand said
late weather balloon data indicated the velocities and directions
of shifting winds were too high to be safe. Wind velocities were
not reported.
   A new launch date was scheduled for 7:51 p.m. Sunday.
   Packed in the nose of the $30 million, 12-story rocket is a $65
million Navstar Global Positioning System satellite, which will
enable military units such as ships, planes, submarines and tanks
to determine their location within 50 feet and in some cases to
within 10 feet.
   The satellite will also keep track of their speed within a
fraction of a mile per hour and the precise time within a millionth
of a second.
   American and allied military users will receive information from
a coded channel. Civilian users, who also have access to the
satellite system, will monitor an open channel that will provide
them with a position accuracy of 300 feet.
   The 3,675-pound Navstar GPS contains an atomic clock with an
error rate of one second every 300,000 years.
   The satellite is the second of 21 upgraded Navstars that the Air
Force plans to orbit to complete a global system by 1992, giving
anyone anywhere in the world 24-hour access to the positioning
information.
   The first advanced Navstar was launched aboard the maiden flight
of the Delta 2 on Feb. 14.
   Seven earlier model Navstar satellites are orbiting the Earth.
The new model has more power and improved systems and has added the
coded military channel.
   The Delta 2 is a more powerful version of the earlier Delta
rocket that has been flying since 1960, logging 170 successes in
182 launches.
   It is one of at least 54 new unmanned rockets the Pentagon is
ordering in a $14 billion program to resolve a post-Challenger
crisis that left about 40 reconnaissance and other national
security payloads languishing in storage for want of a launch
vehicle.
   The backlog was created by the grounding of the space shuttle
fleet for 32 months after the 1986 Challenger explosion. The
Defense Department decided after the accident that it could not
rely solely on the shuttle for access to space and ordered
development of the Delta 2 and a more powerful Titan 4 rocket.
   The Air Force originally had planned to launch all 21 of the
advanced Navstars on the shuttle. All now will fly on Delta 2s.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890520-0119 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-20-89 2215EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Zimbabwe     05-20 0359</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Zimbabwe,0368</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Deny New Political Party Authority to Stage Rallies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN EDLIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HARARE, Zimbabwe (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Zimbabwe police have denied permission
for a new opposition political party to hold its first public
rallies Sunday to explain why it seeks to replace President Robert
Mugabe's socialist government.
   Edgar Tekere's Zimbabwe Unity Movement (ZUM) was formed last
month with pledges to fight mounting top-level official corruption,
campaign against President Mugabe's aim of establishing a one-party
state next year and halt the march to socialism.
   Tekere, who intended to explain his party's policies at two
separate football stadiums in Harare, was a founder of Mugabe's
governing Zimbabwe African National Union (Patriotic Front) party
in 1963.
   A onetime secretary-general of the governing party, Tekere, 52,
was fired from the politburo and the central committee in October
after publicly denouncing corruption and charging that politicians
were building a personality cult around Mugabe. He founded the
oppposition party on April 30.
   The Herald newspaper, published in Harare by the
state-controlled Mass Media Trust, reported Saturday that police
had turned down Tekere's applications for permission to hold the
rallies.
   Under Zimbabwean law, all political gatherings have to be
cleared in advance by the police. Authorities have denied similar
requests by other opposition parties in the past, usually arguing
that they could trigger tensions between rival political supporters.
   ``They did request permission to hold the rallies and the police
did not approve,'' Chief Operations Staff Officer Emmanuel Ruzario
was quoted as saying. ``ZUM were notified of the police decision
within seven days ... We said no.''
   A spokesman for Tekere, speaking on condition of anonymity, said
ZUM would fight the ban in the courts.
   Tekere has declined to say how many members he has in a country
with only three other active political parties. Former Tekere
loyalists have said the formation of ZUM will only create divisions
in Zimbabwe, a British colony until independence nine years ago.
   Mugabe has promised he will transform Zimbabwe into a one-party
state next year after a formal merger of the two main parties, his
own and the Zimbabwe African People's Union (Patriotic Front), in
August.
</TEXT>
