<HEAD>Police Arrest Eight at Klan Rally in Pennsylvania</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LAN1</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EPHRATA, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ku Klux Klansmen held a recruitment rally
Saturday but drew mostly bottles and cans thrown by protesters.
Police arrested eight people.
   More than 40 police officers, including state police in riot
gear and mounted officers, turned out for the rally by about 25
Klansmen at Ephrata Community Park in this city about 50 miles west
of Philadelphia. About 300 people watched from behind police lines
   About 10 minutes into the rally, two men threw bottles and cans
at Klansmen on the other side of a security fence. The two were
arrested.
   Fifteen minutes later, about 15 members of the New York
City-based International Committee Against Racism arrived with
signs and bullhorns, and tried to shout down the robed Klansmen
with such slogans as ``Death to the Klan.'' Klansmen made no move
toward the counterdemonstrators.
   Most of those arrested belonged to the anti-racism group.
   Six people were charged with disorderly conduct, one with
resisting arrest and disorderly conduct and one with public
drunkenness, said police Sgt. Brian Kurtz.
