<FIRST>r i AM-HongKong-China     05-20 0382</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hong Kong-China,0392</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hong Kong Fears Unrest in China Could Affect its Future</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hong Kong reacted nervously Saturday to China's
declaration of martial law, fearing the move might mean Beijing
will restrict freedoms in this British colony when it comes under
Chinese sovereignty in eight years.
   Under a Chinese-British agreement signed in 1984, China has
promised to preserve Hong Kong's capitalist lifestyle for 50 years
beyond 1997 under a unique ``one country, two systems'' formula.
   Chinese Premier Li Peng declared martial law in parts of the
capital Saturday after authorities were unable to quell massive
student-led protests for democratic reform.
   Liberal groups in Hong Kong condemned the decision, urging
residents to shelve their political differences and support the
student movement.
   They said the failure of the student movement could affect Hong
Kong's future and weaken China's promises to retain the
free-wheeling socioeconomic system that has made the colony a world
financial center.
   ``If they go against the freedom of human rights, Hong Kong
people will lose confidence in the (Chinese) government,'' said Lam
Wai-keung, a member of the lawmaking Legislative Council.
   Businessmen say Hong Kong's economy could suffer should the
situation in China deteriorate further, especially if clashes erupt
between students and the military.
   Hong Kong depends on China for its food and trade, and its
economy and stock market react violently to political developments
on the mainland.
   On Friday, the Hang Seng stock index plummeted 132.03 points in
panic selling over news from China, including the reported
resignation of Communist Party General Secretary Zhao Ziyang. The
moderate Zhao had pushed for a compromise with the students.
   It was the worst single-day plunge since the worldwide market
collapse in October 1987. Brokers say the market could suffer
further when it opens Monday unless the crisis in China stabilizes.
   For Hong Kong's 5.7 million residents, 98 percent of whom are
Chinese, the thought of a future under Communism is a haunting one.
   An estimated two-thirds of them are refugees from China or their
descendants, who fled from despair or political persecution on the
mainland.
   A poll conducted by the conservative English-language South
China Morning Post earlier this month said one-third of Hong Kong's
population is considering emigrating before the territory reverts
to China in 1997.
</TEXT>
