<FIRST>r a AM-SeabrookProtest     05-20 0209</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Seabrook Protest,0217</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Arrested After Hanging Banner at Seabrook</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEABROOK, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police on Saturday arrested two protesters
who scaled a fence surrounding the Seabrook nuclear power plant and
spent six hours atop a tower that supports high-voltage power lines.
   The demonstrators hung a banner from two legs of the tower
urging people to oppose low-power tests, which could start this
month at the reactor.
   Seabrook spokesman Rob Williams denounced the action as ``very
irresponsible'' and dangerous. But Seabrook police said they saw no
reason to forcibly remove Harry Leno, 52, of Ipswich, Mass., and
Christopher Nord, 36, of Merrimac, Mass., from the tower.
   The protesters climbed about 50 feet up the tower, but were
``nowhere near'' the 345,000-volt power line above them, said
Seabrook police Sgt. David Currier.
   ``It was certainly no danger,'' Currier said. ``We would have
simply left them up there until they got tired.''
   When they came down, Leno and Nord were charged with criminal
trespass, issued summonses and released.
   The Nuclear Regulatory Commission gave final approval to a
low-power license last week. A federal appeals court is reviewing a
request by Seabrook foes to delay the tests.
   Protests against Seabrook have resulted in about 2,500 arrests
since construction began in 1976.
