<FIRST>r i AM-HungaryReform     05-20 0300</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hungary Reform,0309</SECOND>
<HEAD>Communist Party Reformers Open Conference</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALEX BANDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SZEGED, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 400 Communist Party members
demanding reforms on Saturday opened a two-day national conference
in this southern Hungarian city.
   It was a followup to an unprecedented meeting in Kecskemet on
April 15 when the reformers questioned the future of the party that
has ruled the country since the end of World War II.
   Gyorgy Kerenyi, a party leader in eastern Hungary said in his
opening address:
   ``We don't want to leave it (the party), we want to take it
over, thus paving the way for a massive transformation to bring
about a self-reliant, democratic and socialist party.
   ``The party needs a leadership that both listens to its members
and lets them decide. We've had enough of the sneaky and stealthy
way of doing politics.''
   Jozsef Geczi, a representative of the Csongrad district, said
Hungary's Communist Party cannot rid itself of the model built by
Josef Stalin, the late Soviet dictator, ``until it changes its own
internal mechanism and structure.''
   He said that would require the convening of a special party
congress next fall.
   Organizers said the conference was divided into five workshops
to consider the decades of one-party rule, the transition to a
democratic constitution and economic policies.
   Gyorgy Kerekes, a Budapest sociologist, said the conference has
gone ``well beyond the get-acquainted'' session in Kecskemet.
   He said members are debating the role of a younger generation
``who want no share of the stigma of the past'' but want to take
responsibility for the present and future.
   ``They feel they must either succeed in reforming the party
within the next few months and put the reformers in the lead or,
failing that, quit the party and start an independent left-wing
political party.''

