<FILEID>AP-NR-05-20-89 0100EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a f BC-BeerBattles Adv22   05-20 0863</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Beer Battles, Adv 22,0890</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv22</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Monday, May 22 and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Beer Companies Beginning to Take Offensive In Alcohol Battles</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserGraphic planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JONATHAN YENKIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MILWAUKEE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Beer drinkers will see two messages this year _
one telling them alcohol consumption may cause health problems, and
the other claiming beer is ``as basic as bread.''
   While the first message will appear on government warning labels
on alcoholic beverage containers, the second will be included in
advertisements by Anheuser-Busch Cos. Inc., the nation's largest
brewer.
   Anheuser, however, is not alone in defending its product. In an
industry battered by concerns over alcohol abuse and drunken
driving, some executives have decided to fight back and tell the
public that beer not only is safe but has a revered place in
cultural history.
   ``Most of the action has been on the playing field of the
critics,'' said James Sanders, president of the Beer Institute, a
trade association in Washington. ``We need to get out of the
reactive mode and into a proactive mode.''
   The U.S. beer industry has been stagnant in recent years, and
analysts say one cause has been a changing social attitude toward
drinking and a greater awareness of alcohol's potential hazards.
   But industry officials say they have been portrayed too often as
villains, and they say beer can be enjoyed safely if consumed
responsibly.
   ``Beer drinkers are not drug addicts,'' Leonard Goldstein,
president of Miller Brewing Co., said in an April speech to
Wisconsin beer distributors. ``Throughout history, beer has
provided lots of enjoyment for millions of consumers.''
   But, he added, ``if ever there was a time for our industry to
pull together and fight for control of our own destiny, that time
is now.''
   Last December, the U.S. Surgeon General's office held a workshop
on drunk driving and issued preliminary recommendations, which
Goldstein called ``an obituary for the alcohol beverage industry.''
   Among them were measures to ban alcohol advertisements by
celebrities ``who have a strong appeal to youth,'' and to create
equal time for public service spots to balance the advertising of
alcoholic products. Final recommendations will be included in a
report due May 31.
   Also last year, Congress passed the alcohol labeling law, which
takes effect in November. Labels on beverage containers will alert
people to the hazards of drinking while pregnant and warn how
alcohol can impair the ability to drive or operate machinery.
   A major supporter of alcohol labeling has been the Center for
Science in the Public Interest, a consumer advocacy group in
Washington. The center also has lobbied Congress for higher excise
taxes on alcohol.
   ``We're not interested in curtailing all alcohol use, in the
sense of being neo-prohibitionists,'' said Karen Lieberman, who
works on the center's alcohol policies project. ``We want to curb
alcohol problems.''
   Similarly, Micky Sadoff, president of Mothers Against Drunk
Driving, said: ``We've never taken a position against alcohol in
general. I drink myself.
   ``We're talking about the combination of alcohol and driving,
and flying, and boating and snowmobiling.''
   But beer industry officials, who share concerns about alcohol
abuse and drunken driving, have opposed the labeling law as a scare
tactic.
   ``We think it's not a contribution,'' said Sanders, of the Beer
Institute. ``You don't tell the whole story in a couple of words.''
   ``You might have young people who think that their parents who
open a beer at dinner are drug pushers,'' he said.
   The Beer Institute is planning a promotion to ``give the true
story of the beer industry,'' Sanders said. ``If beer is treated
with good sense, it works itself into a healthy lifestyle.''
   Anheuser, based in St. Louis, is expanding its ``Know when to
say when'' ad campaign aimed at responsible drinking. In addition,
the company will incorporate a message of moderation into another
campaign, to begin running later this year, which will trace the
tradition of beer through history.
   One ad will use early American paintings to show how beer was
brought to America on the Mayflower, was used to celebrate the
first Thanksgiving and was part of the daily ration for soldiers in
the American Revolution.
   A second ad, which shows how the art of brewing has passed down
through centuries, contains this line: ``It's older than the
written word and as basic as bread.''
   ``It talks about the heritage and the quality of beer,'' said
Steve Burrows, staff vice president in marketing at Anheuser.
``We've taken that quality message and put in a responsible
drinking message.''
   Such promotions could help push the pendulum of public opinion
in the beer industry's direction, said Anita Rosepka, senior editor
of Beverage Media, a trade publication in New York.
   ``I think the industry has had the attitude that publicity will
swing back to normal,'' she said. ``But now it's the time to do
something. It's gone on too long.''
   ``Their attempts are notable,'' Lieberman said, referring to the
beer companies' promotions of responsible drinking. ``But their
messages fall far short.''
   She said even statements like ``know when to say when''
encourage some use of the product.
   ``There's no message that abstinence is a serious option,'' she
said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End adv for Monday, May 22</NOTE>
