<FILEID>AP-NR-05-20-89 0103EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a f BC-CreditMarkets Adv22   05-20 0608</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Credit Markets, Adv 22,0634</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv22</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Monday May 22</HEAD>
<HEAD>Looking Beyond Food and Energy: Is Inflation Spiral Spinning?</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARYBETH NIBLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The economy should stay on a restricted credit
diet while it works off an inflationary bulge. Breaking the diet
now would keep the economy from getting into good shape.
   At least that's the view of a number of observers who think the
time isn't right for the Federal Reserve Board to dole out bigger
helpings of credit. Current rations are providing sufficient
nourishment for the economy to grow without slipping into a
recession, they say.
   Judging by the mood in the bond market this past week,
professional traders don't necessarily agree with this prescription.
   Bond prices moved up despite word from the Labor Department that
the Consumer Price Index rose 0.7 percent in April. Bonds benefited
from increasing optimism that the Fed soon will be able to loosen
its grip on credit and permit interest rates to fall.
   At first glance, the unexpectedly large CPI reading looked like
bad news for bonds. But traders quickly overcame their initial
shock, comforted from the realization that much of the thrust
behind last month's inflation rate was fueled by the largest
gasoline price surge on record.
   Excluding energy prices, which were affected by supply
disruptions after an Exxon oil tanker beached off the Alaskan
coast, the CPI rose 0.2 percent.
   In the opinion of economist Norman Ture, president of the
Institute for Research on the Economics of Taxation, the special
factors that elevated the April CPI exaggerated the true inflation
rate.
   ``It's very difficult to see any reason for an inflationary
resurgence,'' Ture says.
   He says sentiment in the precious metals market supports this
view. Prices of gold, a commodity that investors frequently turn to
as a hedge against inflation, dropped late last week to the lowest
levels in three years.
   Though he doesn't consider gold prices a reliable gauge of
inflation expectations, Michael Moran, chief economist at Daiwa
Securities America Inc., shares the idea that the worst news on
inflation this year may be over.
   ``My view on inflation is that we'll see a very gradual easing
off of inflation during the course of the year,'' says Moran, a
former Fed economist.
   He says the central bank's credit-tightening actions late last
year and earlier in 1989 were enough to bring inflation under
control. Relaxing the restrictive stance now would risk inflation
getting out of hand, he says.
   So the Fed mustn't react to recent signs of slower economic
growth by immediately driving down interest rates, says Moran.
   ``How should the Fed respond to this situation? I think they
should be very cautious in easing monetary policy,'' he says.
   ``If they were to ease off too early we could get a bounce back
in the economy,'' says Moran, adding ``the risk is greater that
we'll have a pickup in inflation rather than a recesssion.''
   Recession may be all the more unlikely because the dollar's
recent surge is stimulating economic growth and partly countering
the negative impact of higher U.S. interest rates.
   Lacy Hunt, chief economist at the investment firm CM&amp;M Group,
says the strong dollar will spur consumer spending _ if it hasn't
already _ by cutting the price of imported merchandise.
   An inflow of foreign money, lured by the attractive returns that
high U.S. rates imply, could help rejuvenate the housing and other
sectors of the economy bruised by rising credit costs, Hunt says.
   For these reasons, he says, ``the inflation number was bad but
it didn't matter because of the surging dollar.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Monday, May 22</NOTE>
